VALUES ('6414c299-299e-4c0f-8c3b-e0db3476b095', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 about urban beekeeping?', 'Text 1
City rooftops are an ideal home for honeybees. With so many gardens, parks, and flowering balconies nearby, urban bees have plenty of flowers to visit. Many cities now encourage residents to keep hives on their roofs.

Text 2
When too many hives are placed in a single neighborhood, the honeybees must compete with wild bees for the same limited flowers. Some researchers warn that crowding urban areas with managed hives can actually leave native pollinators hungry.', '[{"id":"A","text":"By agreeing that city rooftops provide unlimited flowers for all bees","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 states flowers are ''limited,'' so its author would not agree they are unlimited."},{"id":"B","text":"By cautioning that placing many hives in one area can harm wild bees","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 2 directly warns that ''crowding urban areas with managed hives can actually leave native pollinators hungry,'' which is a caution about the rooftop hives Text 1 praises."},{"id":"C","text":"By recommending that cities ban all rooftop gardens","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 never mentions banning gardens; it focuses on the number of hives, not gardens."},{"id":"D","text":"By insisting that wild bees do not visit city flowers at all","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says wild bees ''compete'' for the flowers, which means they do visit them."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Text 1 celebrates urban hives because cities offer ''plenty of flowers.'' Text 2''s author would respond with a caution, since Text 2 warns that ''crowding urban areas with managed hives can actually leave native pollinators hungry'' when ''too many hives are placed in a single neighborhood.'' This adds a concern about the very practice Text 1 encourages.', 'Find the warning in Text 2 and ask how it complicates Text 1''s enthusiasm.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('3bbc2599-ef8a-422f-9268-5b502e690fbd', 'How does Text 2 relate to the information presented in Text 1?', 'Text 1
For many years, scientists believed that the giant squid was a slow, sluggish creature that simply drifted through the deep ocean. Its enormous size seemed to suggest a calm, unhurried way of moving.

Text 2
Recent video footage captured a giant squid lunging quickly to seize its prey. Marine biologists who watched the recording noted that the animal moved with surprising speed and power.', '[{"id":"A","text":"It provides evidence that challenges the earlier belief described in Text 1.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 2''s footage of a squid ''lunging quickly'' and moving with ''surprising speed'' contradicts Text 1''s claim that the squid was ''slow, sluggish'' and ''drifted.''"},{"id":"B","text":"It offers additional examples that confirm the belief described in Text 1.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 contradicts rather than confirms Text 1, since it shows fast movement, not sluggishness."},{"id":"C","text":"It explains why the scientists in Text 1 first studied the giant squid.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says nothing about why scientists began studying squid; it reports new observed behavior."},{"id":"D","text":"It restates the claim in Text 1 using more technical language.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 does not restate Text 1''s claim; it presents an opposing observation."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Text 1 describes the long-held belief that the giant squid was ''slow, sluggish'' and ''simply drifted.'' Text 2 presents new evidence undercutting that view: footage showed the squid ''lunging quickly to seize its prey'' and moving ''with surprising speed and power.'' Thus Text 2 challenges the earlier belief in Text 1.', 'Compare the squid''s described speed in each text.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('501fbdb6-6726-4316-bd9f-abba2de53461', 'Which choice best describes the relationship between the two texts?', 'Text 1
Many people assume that yawning happens only when we are tired or bored. After a long day, a wide yawn often feels like a signal that the body is ready for sleep.

Text 2
Researchers have found that people also yawn when they feel too warm. By drawing in cool air, a yawn may help lower the temperature of the brain, keeping it working efficiently.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Text 2 presents an additional cause of yawning not mentioned in Text 1.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 1 links yawning to being ''tired or bored,'' while Text 2 adds a different cause—feeling ''too warm''—that Text 1 does not mention."},{"id":"B","text":"Text 2 argues that the cause of yawning in Text 1 is completely false.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says people ''also'' yawn when warm, adding to rather than rejecting Text 1''s cause."},{"id":"C","text":"Text 2 provides a personal story that illustrates Text 1''s claim.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 reports research findings, not a personal story, and concerns a new cause."},{"id":"D","text":"Text 2 repeats the same explanation for yawning given in Text 1.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 gives a temperature-based explanation, which differs from Text 1''s tiredness explanation."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Text 1 presents the common idea that yawning signals tiredness or boredom. Text 2 introduces a separate cause: ''people also yawn when they feel too warm,'' suggesting a yawn ''may help lower the temperature of the brain.'' The word ''also'' shows Text 2 is adding a cause Text 1 did not include.', 'Notice the word ''also'' in Text 2 and what new reason it introduces.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('7213e896-600f-40cc-8989-4d4be248c308', 'Based on the texts, the author of Text 1 and the author of Text 2 would most likely agree with which statement?', 'Text 1
Learning a second language as an adult can be deeply rewarding. Although progress may feel slow at first, regular practice allows adult learners to hold real conversations within a year.

Text 2
Some believe only children can master a new language, but adults bring advantages of their own. Their experience with grammar and their focused study habits often help them learn quickly when they practice consistently.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Adults cannot learn a new language as well as children can.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Both texts highlight adult success, so neither author would agree adults cannot learn well."},{"id":"B","text":"Consistent practice helps adults succeed at learning a language.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 1 credits ''regular practice'' and Text 2 credits practicing ''consistently,'' so both authors would agree on this point."},{"id":"C","text":"Language learning is only worthwhile for people under the age of ten.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Both texts focus on adult learners, contradicting the idea that only young children should learn."},{"id":"D","text":"Grammar rules make language learning impossible for most adults.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 treats grammar experience as an ''advantage,'' not an obstacle."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Both authors emphasize the role of steady practice in adult language learning. Text 1 says ''regular practice allows adult learners to hold real conversations within a year,'' and Text 2 says adults ''learn quickly when they practice consistently.'' The shared point of agreement is that consistent practice helps adults succeed.', 'Find the one idea about practice that appears in both texts.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('94a35efc-5e5a-4747-ac3e-9f2602501da1', 'How does the main point of Text 2 differ from the main point of Text 1?', 'Text 1
The invention of the printing press is often credited to a single brilliant inventor working alone. Stories tell of one person whose clever design suddenly made books affordable to ordinary readers.

Text 2
In reality, the printing press built on the work of many earlier craftspeople. Improvements in paper, ink, and metalworking, developed over generations, made the famous machine possible.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Text 1 credits one lone inventor, while Text 2 emphasizes many contributors over time.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 1 says the press is credited to ''a single brilliant inventor working alone,'' whereas Text 2 stresses ''the work of many earlier craftspeople'' over generations."},{"id":"B","text":"Text 1 claims books were rare, while Text 2 claims books were never affordable.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 1 actually says the press made books ''affordable,'' and Text 2 does not deny this."},{"id":"C","text":"Text 1 focuses on paper and ink, while Text 2 focuses on a single inventor.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This reverses the texts: paper and ink appear in Text 2, and the single inventor appears in Text 1."},{"id":"D","text":"Text 1 and Text 2 both argue the printing press was invented by accident.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Neither text claims accidental invention, so this describes neither main point."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Text 1 presents the popular story of ''a single brilliant inventor working alone.'' Text 2 corrects this by emphasizing collective effort: the press ''built on the work of many earlier craftspeople,'' with improvements ''developed over generations.'' The key difference is one lone inventor versus many contributors over time.', 'Compare how many people each text credits with the invention.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('4476b6c6-2854-4e93-8672-62d31e17fbd5', 'Which choice best states how Text 2 responds to Text 1?', 'Text 1
Reading on a screen is just as effective as reading on paper. Because the words are identical, students should understand and remember a digital text exactly as well as a printed one.

Text 2
Studies suggest that readers often remember printed pages better than screens. Scrolling and on-screen distractions may make it harder for the brain to form a clear mental map of where information appears.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Text 2 supports Text 1 by adding reasons that screens improve memory.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says readers remember print ''better than screens,'' so it does not support screens improving memory."},{"id":"B","text":"Text 2 disagrees with Text 1 by suggesting print can aid memory more than screens.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 2 directly counters Text 1''s equality claim, stating ''readers often remember printed pages better than screens.''"},{"id":"C","text":"Text 2 agrees with Text 1 that screen and paper reading are identical.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 points out a difference in memory, contradicting the idea that the two are identical."},{"id":"D","text":"Text 2 changes the subject from reading to writing on screens.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 stays focused on reading and memory, not writing."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Text 1 argues that screen reading is ''just as effective as reading on paper'' and that students should remember digital text ''exactly as well.'' Text 2 disagrees, citing studies that ''readers often remember printed pages better than screens'' because scrolling and distractions hinder forming a ''clear mental map.'' Thus Text 2 pushes back against Text 1''s equivalence claim.', 'Decide whether Text 2 says the two formats are equal or different for memory.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('404873b7-506e-44bb-8c5a-25db198272b3', 'Based on the texts, how would Reyes (Text 1) most likely characterize the findings of the municipal study described in Text 2?', 'Text 1
Urban planner Dolores Reyes argues that wide, multilane roads through city centers ultimately worsen traffic. When more lanes are added, she notes, drivers who previously avoided the area begin using it, and within a few years congestion returns to its earlier levels.

Text 2
A recent municipal study tracked a downtown corridor for six years after two lanes were added. Average commute times dropped sharply in the first months but returned to pre-expansion levels by the fourth year, as daily traffic volume rose by nearly forty percent.', '[{"id":"A","text":"As confirming her claim that added road capacity eventually draws enough new drivers to erase any initial gains","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Reyes predicts that new lanes attract previously absent drivers until \"congestion returns to its earlier levels,\" which is exactly what the study found when commute times \"returned to pre-expansion levels by the fourth year\" amid rising traffic."},{"id":"B","text":"As surprising, because she expected widened roads to permanently reduce congestion in city centers","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This reverses Reyes''s view; she explicitly argues that wider roads \"ultimately worsen traffic,\" so the study''s outcome would not surprise her."},{"id":"C","text":"As flawed, because the study measured commute times rather than the number of lanes added","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Reyes never questions the study''s methods, and the study does track lanes added; nothing in either text suggests she would reject the measurement of commute times."},{"id":"D","text":"As incomplete, because the study failed to consider drivers who avoid the area entirely","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The study does account for such drivers by reporting that traffic volume rose \"by nearly forty percent,\" reflecting the new drivers Reyes describes; she would not fault it on this point."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Reyes argues in Text 1 that adding lanes causes "drivers who previously avoided the area" to start using it until "congestion returns to its earlier levels." Text 2''s study found that after two lanes were added, commute times "returned to pre-expansion levels by the fourth year, as daily traffic volume rose by nearly forty percent." The study''s pattern directly matches Reyes''s prediction, so she would view it as confirmation.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'medium', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('f042b20e-2efe-4407-a4b8-89f763726ed2', 'How does Bauer (Text 2) respond to the conclusion Tran draws in Text 1?', 'Text 1
Marine biologist Anh Tran maintains that octopuses solve problems through genuine learning rather than instinct. In her lab, octopuses that watched another individual open a latched jar learned to open it far faster than those given no demonstration, suggesting they absorb information by observation.

Text 2
Researcher Felix Bauer is skeptical of such claims. He argues that what looks like learning by watching may simply reflect an octopus''s strong drive to explore any new object, and that the demonstrated animals might have succeeded faster merely because the jar had already been partly loosened.', '[{"id":"A","text":"By proposing alternative explanations for the same experimental result that Tran attributes to observational learning","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Bauer offers two other causes—an exploratory \"drive to explore any new object\" and a \"partly loosened\" jar—for the faster openings Tran credits to learning by observation."},{"id":"B","text":"By presenting new data showing that octopuses cannot open latched jars at all","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Bauer presents no new experiment or data; he reinterprets Tran''s existing result rather than disproving that octopuses can open jars."},{"id":"C","text":"By agreeing with Tran that octopuses learn by observation but disputing how quickly they do so","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Bauer does not agree that observation is the cause; he is \"skeptical of such claims\" and questions whether learning occurred at all."},{"id":"D","text":"By arguing that Tran''s octopuses were less motivated to explore than the undemonstrated ones","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Bauer attributes the result partly to a strong exploratory drive, not a weaker one, and he does not claim the demonstrated animals were less motivated."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Tran concludes in Text 1 that faster jar-opening after a demonstration shows octopuses "absorb information by observation." In Text 2, Bauer counters not with new data but by offering rival explanations for the same outcome: the animals'' "strong drive to explore any new object" and the fact that "the jar had already been partly loosened." Proposing alternative causes for the identical result is the relationship described in option A.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'medium', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('cc0ec664-14ca-4033-86f3-366a9d6ad995', 'Based on the texts, Nair (Text 1) and Webb (Text 2) would most likely disagree about which of the following?', 'Text 1
Historian Priya Nair contends that the printing press spread literacy mainly because it made books cheap enough for ordinary households. Before the press, she notes, a single hand-copied book could cost as much as a laborer earned in a year, placing reading beyond the reach of all but the wealthy.

Text 2
Historian Marcus Webb emphasizes a different cause. He argues that literacy spread chiefly because reformers built networks of free local schools, and that even cheaply printed books did little good in communities where almost no one had been taught to read them.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Whether the affordability of printed books was the primary driver of expanding literacy","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Nair credits literacy''s spread \"mainly\" to cheap books, while Webb says it spread \"chiefly\" because of free schools and that cheap books \"did little good\" without instruction—a direct clash over the primary cause."},{"id":"B","text":"Whether hand-copied books were expensive before the printing press existed","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Only Nair discusses the cost of hand-copied books; Webb never disputes this point, so it is not a stated disagreement."},{"id":"C","text":"Whether reformers ever built networks of free local schools","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The existence of free schools is asserted only by Webb and is not contradicted by Nair, so the texts do not disagree about it."},{"id":"D","text":"Whether literacy increased after the invention of the printing press","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Both historians accept that literacy spread; they differ on the cause, not on whether the increase occurred."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Nair argues in Text 1 that the press "spread literacy mainly because it made books cheap enough for ordinary households." Webb counters in Text 2 that literacy "spread chiefly because reformers built networks of free local schools," adding that cheap books "did little good" without readers. The two thus disagree specifically about whether book affordability was the primary driver, making A the point of contention.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'medium', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('3305a30f-0e31-434d-a35a-a75ebe640ecf', 'How does the information in Text 2 bear on the uncertainty Okafor raises in Text 1?', 'Text 1
Astronomer Lena Okafor notes that the planet''s faint atmospheric glow could indicate active volcanoes releasing gas. However, she cautions that the same glow could also be produced by sunlight scattering off high-altitude clouds, so the observation alone cannot settle the question.

Text 2
A follow-up survey detected sulfur dioxide concentrated in narrow plumes above three separate surface hot spots on the planet. On Earth, sulfur dioxide in such tightly clustered plumes is released almost exclusively by erupting volcanoes.', '[{"id":"A","text":"It provides evidence favoring the volcanic explanation over the alternative Okafor mentions","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Okafor leaves open whether volcanoes or scattered cloud-light cause the glow; Text 2''s sulfur dioxide \"concentrated in narrow plumes above…hot spots,\" a near-exclusive sign of volcanoes, tips the evidence toward the volcanic cause."},{"id":"B","text":"It confirms that high-altitude clouds, not volcanoes, are responsible for the glow","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The sulfur dioxide plumes point to volcanoes; nothing in Text 2 supports the cloud-scattering explanation, so it does not confirm clouds."},{"id":"C","text":"It shows that Okafor was wrong to consider volcanic activity a possible cause","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Text 2 strengthens the volcanic possibility rather than ruling it out, so Okafor''s consideration of volcanoes is reinforced, not refuted."},{"id":"D","text":"It demonstrates that the atmospheric glow cannot be explained by either of Okafor''s proposals","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Text 2 supports one of Okafor''s two proposals—the volcanic one—rather than eliminating both."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'In Text 1 Okafor says the glow "could indicate active volcanoes" but "could also be produced by sunlight scattering off high-altitude clouds," leaving the cause unresolved. Text 2 reports sulfur dioxide "concentrated in narrow plumes above three separate surface hot spots," a pattern "released almost exclusively by erupting volcanoes." This new evidence favors the volcanic explanation over the cloud alternative, which is exactly what option A states.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'medium', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('57a66537-4778-4ff5-9399-20f209e0a7c4', 'Which choice best describes the relationship between the two texts?', 'Text 1
Education researcher Sam Ortiz argues that frequent low-stakes quizzes help students remember material long after a course ends. The act of retrieving an answer from memory, he claims, strengthens the memory itself far more than simply rereading the same information.

Text 2
In a yearlong classroom trial, students who took brief ungraded quizzes twice a week recalled, six months later, nearly twice as much course content as classmates who spent the same minutes rereading their notes. Both groups had reported feeling equally confident about the material when the course ended.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Text 2 reports experimental results consistent with the general principle Ortiz advances in Text 1","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Ortiz claims retrieval \"strengthens the memory…far more than…rereading,\" and Text 2''s quizzed students \"recalled…nearly twice as much…as classmates who spent the same minutes rereading,\" matching his principle."},{"id":"B","text":"Text 2 challenges Ortiz''s principle by showing rereading produces stronger long-term recall","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Text 2 shows the opposite—quizzed students recalled nearly twice as much as rereaders—so it supports rather than challenges Ortiz."},{"id":"C","text":"Text 2 explains why quizzing strengthens memory, a mechanism Ortiz leaves unaddressed","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Ortiz already supplies the mechanism (retrieval strengthens memory), and Text 2 reports outcomes without explaining the underlying mechanism."},{"id":"D","text":"Text 2 limits Ortiz''s principle by showing it holds only for students who feel confident","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Text 2 notes both groups \"felt equally confident,\" yet their recall differed, so confidence is not presented as a condition that limits the principle."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Ortiz advances in Text 1 the principle that retrieving answers "strengthens the memory itself far more than simply rereading." Text 2 provides a trial in which quizzed students "recalled…nearly twice as much course content as classmates who spent the same minutes rereading their notes." The experimental result aligns with and supports Ortiz''s general claim, which is the relationship captured by option A.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'medium', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('ef2a8a15-f112-4803-ae00-8061423553f3', 'Based on the texts, how do Sanz and Halvorsen differ in their poetic treatment of the sea?', 'Text 1
The poet Aurelio Sanz often portrayed the sea as a comforting presence, describing waves that "fold the tired shore in their patient arms" and tides that return "like a promise kept each evening." For Sanz, the ocean''s rhythms offered reassurance and a sense of order.

Text 2
Sanz''s contemporary, the poet Mira Halvorsen, wrote of the same coastline very differently. In her verses the sea is restless and threatening, "gnawing the cliffs to ruin" and dragging "all that we love past the reach of our hands."', '[{"id":"A","text":"Sanz presents the sea as soothing and dependable, whereas Halvorsen presents it as menacing and destructive","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Sanz''s sea is \"comforting,\" with tides \"like a promise kept,\" while Halvorsen''s is \"restless and threatening,\" \"gnawing the cliffs to ruin\"—a contrast between reassurance and menace."},{"id":"B","text":"Sanz focuses on the sea''s effect on sailors, whereas Halvorsen focuses on its effect on the shore","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Neither text mentions sailors; both poets write about the sea''s relationship to the shore and cliffs, so this distinction is unsupported."},{"id":"C","text":"Sanz describes the sea using precise scientific detail, whereas Halvorsen relies on vague impressions","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Both poets use figurative, emotional language (\"patient arms,\" \"gnawing the cliffs\"); neither offers scientific detail, so the contrast is false."},{"id":"D","text":"Sanz views the sea as constantly changing, whereas Halvorsen views it as unchanging and still","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This reverses the texts: Halvorsen''s sea is \"restless\" and active, not still, while Sanz emphasizes its dependable, orderly rhythms."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Text 1 describes Sanz''s sea as "a comforting presence" whose tides return "like a promise kept each evening," offering "reassurance and a sense of order." Text 2 describes Halvorsen''s sea as "restless and threatening," "gnawing the cliffs to ruin" and dragging "all that we love past the reach of our hands." The contrast is between a soothing, dependable ocean and a menacing, destructive one, exactly as option A states.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'medium', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('9c16a08d-8810-41e7-987f-83a116f85906', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the "central claim" presented in Text 1?', 'Text 1
For decades, conservation biologists assumed that the most effective way to protect a threatened species was to safeguard a single, large, contiguous tract of habitat. A unified reserve, the reasoning went, supports a bigger population and avoids the edge effects and isolation that plague smaller parcels. This principle became a near-orthodoxy in reserve design.

Text 2
Recent fieldwork on fragmented woodlands has complicated this picture. Ferreira and colleagues found that several smaller, dispersed reserves can collectively harbor more species than a single reserve of equal total area, because each fragment captures a distinct subset of local conditions. The benefit, however, evaporated for species requiring vast home ranges, which declined sharply in the fragmented landscapes.', '[{"id":"A","text":"It would fully endorse the claim, since Ferreira and colleagues confirmed that contiguous tracts support larger populations.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 does not confirm Text 1''s claim; Ferreira''s central finding is that dispersed reserves can hold MORE species than one equal-area reserve, which complicates rather than endorses the single-reserve principle."},{"id":"B","text":"It would reject the claim outright, arguing that single large reserves are always inferior to fragmented ones.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This overstates Text 2''s position. Text 2 notes the fragmentation benefit \"evaporated for species requiring vast home ranges,\" so it does not hold that single reserves are ALWAYS inferior."},{"id":"C","text":"It would qualify the claim, noting that the single-reserve advantage holds for some species but not for biodiversity as a whole.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 2 shows dispersed reserves can harbor more species overall, yet wide-ranging species \"declined sharply\" in fragmented landscapes, so it accepts the single-reserve logic only for that subset, qualifying Text 1''s near-orthodoxy."},{"id":"D","text":"It would dismiss the claim as irrelevant, since reserve size has no measurable effect on species survival.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 treats size and configuration as highly consequential, reporting sharp declines for wide-ranging species, so it does not regard reserve size as irrelevant."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Text 1 presents the near-orthodox claim that one large contiguous reserve is the most effective design. Text 2 complicates this: dispersed reserves "can collectively harbor more species than a single reserve of equal total area," undercutting the universality of the claim, yet the benefit "evaporated for species requiring vast home ranges, which declined sharply." The author of Text 2 would therefore neither fully endorse nor reject Text 1, but qualify it - the single-large-reserve advantage survives only for wide-ranging species, not for total biodiversity. This matches C.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'hard', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('2a4ad297-685f-4574-b719-939dd8f6b65b', 'How does the perspective of the historian in Text 2 differ from that of the economist in Text 1?', 'Text 1
Economic historians often credit the rapid spread of the printing press in the fifteenth century to falling production costs. As metal type, cheaper paper, and standardized presses lowered the price of a finished book, demand surged, and printing houses multiplied across Europe to meet it. On this account, the technology diffused because it became affordable.

Text 2
Growth in print, I argue, preceded the steepest cost declines rather than following them. Long before paper prices fell, urban merchant networks were already circulating manuscripts intensively, cultivating a reading public hungry for cheap reproductions. The press spread fastest precisely where such networks were densest, suggesting that an existing appetite for texts, not affordability alone, drove its adoption.', '[{"id":"A","text":"The historian identifies a preexisting cultural demand as the primary driver, whereas the economist emphasizes falling costs.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 2 argues the press \"spread fastest precisely where such networks were densest,\" pointing to \"an existing appetite for texts\" as the driver, while Text 1 credits the spread to books becoming \"affordable\" - a direct contrast in primary cause."},{"id":"B","text":"The historian denies that printing spread at all, while the economist documents its rapid diffusion.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 explicitly references \"growth in print\" and the press spreading \"fastest,\" so the historian agrees printing diffused; the disagreement is about cause, not whether it happened."},{"id":"C","text":"The historian attributes the spread to government subsidies, whereas the economist attributes it to merchant wealth.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Neither text mentions government subsidies; Text 2 cites merchant networks as conduits of demand, not as a subsidy mechanism, so this misreads both passages."},{"id":"D","text":"The historian and economist agree on the cause but disagree about the timing of cost declines.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"They disagree on cause itself - demand versus affordability - not merely timing; the timing point in Text 2 is evidence for its causal claim, not a standalone area of agreement."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Text 1''s economist holds that the press "diffused because it became affordable," foregrounding falling production costs. Text 2''s historian counters that growth "preceded the steepest cost declines" and that the press "spread fastest precisely where such networks were densest," concluding that "an existing appetite for texts, not affordability alone, drove its adoption." The core difference is the identified primary driver: preexisting cultural demand (Text 2) versus falling costs (Text 1), which is exactly A.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'hard', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('39b71dda-2b6c-4270-a033-891741d6dbab', 'Which choice best describes the relationship between the findings reported in the two texts?', 'Text 1
In a study of decision-making, participants who were asked to justify their choices aloud tended to select options that were easiest to explain, even when those options were not the ones they had initially preferred. The researchers concluded that the demand for verbal justification can distort preferences, nudging people toward whatever seems most defensible.

Text 2
A later experiment varied who the audience was. When participants justified choices to a sympathetic listener who shared their tastes, the shift toward easily explained options disappeared; their selections matched their private preferences closely. Only when the audience was unfamiliar did the distortion reemerge.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Text 2 disproves Text 1 by showing that verbal justification never alters preferences.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 does not show justification never alters preferences; \"the distortion reemerge[d]\" with unfamiliar audiences, so the effect persists under some conditions and is not disproven."},{"id":"B","text":"Text 2 identifies a condition that limits the generality of Text 1''s conclusion without contradicting its core observation.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 2 finds the distortion \"disappeared\" with a sympathetic listener but reemerged with an unfamiliar one, specifying the audience as a boundary condition while preserving Text 1''s finding that justification can distort preferences."},{"id":"C","text":"Text 2 provides an independent example that has no bearing on the mechanism proposed in Text 1.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 directly tests the same justification mechanism by varying the audience, so it bears closely on Text 1 rather than being unrelated."},{"id":"D","text":"Text 2 confirms Text 1 by reproducing the distortion under every audience condition tested.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 reports the distortion \"disappeared\" with a sympathetic, like-minded listener, so it did not reproduce the effect under every condition; this misstates the result."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Text 1 concludes that "the demand for verbal justification can distort preferences." Text 2 refines this by varying the audience: with a sympathetic, like-minded listener "the shift toward easily explained options disappeared," and "only when the audience was unfamiliar did the distortion reemerge." Thus Text 2 specifies a condition (audience familiarity) that bounds when Text 1''s effect appears, limiting its generality without contradicting the underlying observation that justification CAN distort preferences. This is B.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'hard', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('7b397a9f-34fa-42f0-be2f-9adf60fa8495', 'The author of Text 1 would most likely characterize the conclusion drawn in Text 2 as', 'Text 1
When a new predator is introduced to an island, ecologists frequently observe an immediate crash in native prey populations and conclude that the predator is driving the decline. But such snapshots can mislead. Prey numbers often fluctuate for reasons unrelated to predation, and a crash that coincides with a predator''s arrival may reflect a drought or disease that began earlier.

Text 2
On Marlow Island, the native ground bird collapsed within two years of the rats'' arrival, and we therefore attribute the collapse to predation by rats. The timing is unambiguous: the decline tracked the rats'' spread across the island almost exactly, beginning in the colonized zones and reaching the far coast last.', '[{"id":"A","text":"premature, because the close timing alone cannot rule out an independent cause.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Although Text 1 warns about timing coincidences in general, Text 2 supplies a spatial pattern - the decline \"beginning in the colonized zones and reaching the far coast last\" - which addresses the very coincidence worry, so Text 1 would not call it merely premature."},{"id":"B","text":"persuasive, because the spatial tracking of the decline addresses the very confound Text 1 warns against.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 1''s caution is that a coincidental crash \"may reflect a drought or disease that began earlier\"; Text 2''s evidence that the decline tracked the rats'' spread \"beginning in the colonized zones and reaching the far coast last\" rules out an island-wide independent cause, satisfying Text 1''s standard."},{"id":"C","text":"irrelevant, because Text 1 denies that predators ever cause prey declines.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 1 never denies predators can cause declines; it cautions that some apparent cases reflect other factors, so Text 2''s conclusion is relevant to its concern, not irrelevant."},{"id":"D","text":"unsupported, because Text 2 offers no evidence about the timing of the bird''s collapse.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 explicitly provides timing and spatial evidence - the collapse \"within two years\" tracking the rats'' spread - so the claim that it offers no such evidence is false."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Text 1 warns that a prey crash coinciding with a predator''s arrival "may reflect a drought or disease that began earlier" - an island-wide independent cause. Text 2 anticipates exactly this confound by reporting that the decline "tracked the rats'' spread across the island almost exactly, beginning in the colonized zones and reaching the far coast last." A drought or disease would not propagate in lockstep with the rats'' geographic spread, so this spatial evidence neutralizes Text 1''s specific objection. Text 1''s author would therefore find Text 2 persuasive precisely because it addresses that confound, making B correct.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'hard', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('57aadec0-ef41-43db-bdbe-6d89d5565057', 'Based on the texts, the researcher in Text 2 would most likely argue that the recommendation in Text 1 is', 'Text 1
Many productivity experts advise workers to batch similar tasks together - answering all emails in one block, making all phone calls in another - to minimize the mental cost of switching between different kinds of work. By grouping like with like, they argue, a worker preserves focus and completes more in less time.

Text 2
In our trials, batching improved output only for tasks that drew on the same cognitive resources. When ostensibly "similar" tasks actually competed for the same narrow capacity - as when two activities both demanded intense verbal reasoning - batching them produced more fatigue and errors, not less. Surface similarity, we found, is a poor guide to what should be grouped.', '[{"id":"A","text":"sound in principle but in need of a more precise criterion for which tasks count as similar.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 2 accepts that batching \"improved output\" for genuinely compatible tasks yet warns that \"surface similarity is a poor guide,\" so it would endorse Text 1''s principle while demanding a sharper definition of similarity based on cognitive resources."},{"id":"B","text":"entirely mistaken, since grouping tasks always increases fatigue and errors.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 states batching \"improved output\" when tasks drew on the same resources without competing, so it does not hold that grouping always increases fatigue; this overgeneralizes the finding."},{"id":"C","text":"valuable only for workers who handle exclusively verbal tasks.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 uses verbal reasoning as an example of competing tasks where batching backfires, not as the condition under which the advice is valuable, so this inverts the text''s point."},{"id":"D","text":"well supported, because the trials confirmed that surface similarity reliably predicts which tasks to batch.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 concludes the opposite - that \"surface similarity is a poor guide\" - so it does not confirm surface similarity as a reliable predictor."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Text 1 recommends batching "similar tasks" judged by surface kind (emails together, calls together) to cut switching costs. Text 2 finds the benefit real but conditional: batching "improved output only for tasks that drew on the same cognitive resources," and when superficially similar tasks "competed for the same narrow capacity" it "produced more fatigue and errors." Its verdict that "surface similarity is a poor guide" means the researcher would accept Text 1''s underlying logic but insist on a better criterion for what counts as similar - sound in principle yet needing a more precise standard. That is A.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'hard', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('5a35db82-dab3-4215-bca5-840c9c10246a', 'Which choice best states how Text 2 functions in relation to the argument in Text 1?', 'Text 1
Proponents of replacing letter grades with written feedback argue that grades reduce learning to a single number, encouraging students to chase marks rather than mastery. Remove the grade, they claim, and students will attend to the substantive comments that actually help them improve.

Text 2
When one university dropped grades in favor of narrative evaluations, students did read the comments more closely at first. But many soon reported feeling unable to gauge their standing, and a number requested informal rankings from instructors. The comments were valued; the absence of any comparative marker, it seems, created an anxiety the reform had not anticipated.', '[{"id":"A","text":"It supplies empirical support that strengthens Text 1''s central recommendation without reservation.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 reports an \"anxiety the reform had not anticipated\" and students requesting rankings, which complicates rather than uniformly strengthens Text 1''s recommendation."},{"id":"B","text":"It presents an outcome that partly validates Text 1''s premise while exposing a consequence its argument overlooked.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Text 2 confirms students \"did read the comments more closely,\" validating Text 1''s premise that removing grades draws attention to feedback, yet reveals that losing a \"comparative marker\" produced unanticipated anxiety, a consequence Text 1''s argument ignored."},{"id":"C","text":"It refutes Text 1 by demonstrating that students ignored the written feedback entirely.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says students \"did read the comments more closely\" and that \"the comments were valued,\" so it does not show feedback was ignored; this contradicts the passage."},{"id":"D","text":"It restates Text 1''s reasoning using a specific institutional example that reaches the same conclusion.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 does not reach the same conclusion; it surfaces a drawback - reform-induced anxiety - that diverges from Text 1''s optimistic claim, so it is not a mere restatement."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Text 1 argues that removing grades will lead students to "attend to the substantive comments that actually help them improve." Text 2 partly confirms this premise - "students did read the comments more closely at first" and "the comments were valued" - but then exposes an overlooked consequence: without grades, "many soon reported feeling unable to gauge their standing," and "the absence of any comparative marker...created an anxiety the reform had not anticipated." Text 2 thus both validates part of Text 1''s reasoning and reveals a cost the argument failed to foresee, which is precisely B.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'hard', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('6e9213ae-5463-454e-8881-0ce69a0ad917', 'Which choice most effectively uses information from the text to support Dr. Ortiz''s argument?', 'Marine biologist Dr. Lena Ortiz studies how sea otters affect kelp forests along the Pacific coast. She argues that sea otters play a crucial role in keeping kelp forests healthy. Sea otters feed heavily on sea urchins, which would otherwise multiply and devour large amounts of kelp.', '[{"id":"A","text":"By eating sea urchins, sea otters prevent the urchins from consuming and destroying the kelp.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This directly links the otters'' behavior described in the text (''feed heavily on sea urchins, which would otherwise multiply and devour large amounts of kelp'') to the claim that otters keep kelp forests healthy."},{"id":"B","text":"Sea otters are found along many parts of the Pacific coast.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The otters'' geographic range does not explain how they keep kelp forests healthy, which is the argument that must be supported."},{"id":"C","text":"Kelp forests provide shelter for many different species of fish.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. While true to the topic of kelp forests, this says nothing about the otters'' role, so it cannot support Dr. Ortiz''s specific argument."},{"id":"D","text":"Sea urchins are capable of reproducing very quickly.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This describes urchins alone and omits the otters entirely, failing to support the claim about the otters'' crucial role."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The text states that sea otters ''feed heavily on sea urchins, which would otherwise multiply and devour large amounts of kelp.'' Option A uses exactly this information to show how otters keep kelp forests healthy: by eating the urchins, otters stop the urchins from destroying the kelp.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('73282e6c-506e-43ab-a6f0-38bd7de37611', 'Which finding, if true, would most directly support the archaeologists'' conclusion?', 'A team of archaeologists excavated a settlement in present-day Turkey that was occupied roughly 9,000 years ago. They concluded that the people who lived there had begun to farm rather than rely solely on hunting and gathering. Among the artifacts they uncovered were grinding stones and storage pits filled with the charred remains of cultivated wheat and barley.', '[{"id":"A","text":"The remains of cultivated wheat and barley were found in the settlement''s storage pits.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Cultivated grains stored at the site directly indicate farming, supporting the conclusion that the inhabitants had begun to farm."},{"id":"B","text":"The settlement was located near a river that flooded each spring.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. A nearby river is a feature of the location but does not by itself show that the people were farming."},{"id":"C","text":"Bones of wild deer were discovered scattered throughout the settlement.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Wild deer bones point to hunting, which is the opposite of the farming conclusion the archaeologists reached."},{"id":"D","text":"The settlement contained dwellings built from mud bricks.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The building material of the homes is unrelated to whether the inhabitants grew their own food."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The conclusion is that the inhabitants ''had begun to farm.'' The presence of ''cultivated wheat and barley'' in storage pits is direct evidence of farming, since cultivated grains must be deliberately grown, making option A the strongest support.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('6814c5b9-294b-4c9a-85e1-45232b793016', 'Which choice most effectively uses data from the text to support the researchers'' conclusion?', 'In a recent study, researchers tested whether listening to music while studying affects how well students remember new vocabulary. Students who studied in silence recalled an average of 18 out of 25 words on a later test, while students who studied with music playing recalled an average of 12 out of 25 words. The researchers concluded that background music can interfere with memorizing new vocabulary.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Students who studied with music recalled fewer words (12 out of 25) than students who studied in silence (18 out of 25).","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This contrast in scores shows the music group performed worse, directly supporting the claim that music can interfere with memorization."},{"id":"B","text":"Students who studied in silence recalled an average of 18 out of 25 words.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This single figure does not include the music group''s score, so it cannot show that music interfered with memory."},{"id":"C","text":"Both groups of students were tested on the same set of 25 vocabulary words.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This describes the test''s fairness but provides no data comparing the two groups'' performance."},{"id":"D","text":"Students in both groups studied the vocabulary for the same amount of time.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Equal study time is a study condition, not evidence about which group remembered more words."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The conclusion is that ''background music can interfere with memorizing.'' Option A pairs both data points from the text (12 of 25 with music versus 18 of 25 in silence) to show the music group remembered fewer words, directly supporting the conclusion.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('6bef42c9-7870-496d-8568-20ab2a39e3b0', 'Which choice most effectively uses information from the text to support von Frisch''s claim?', 'Honeybees communicate the location of food to other bees through a behavior called the waggle dance. Scientist Karl von Frisch claimed that the direction a bee waggles indicates the direction of the food relative to the sun. When a food source was placed directly toward the sun, returning bees waggled straight upward on the vertical honeycomb.', '[{"id":"A","text":"The upward waggle corresponded to a food source positioned in the direction of the sun.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This matches the dance direction (straight up) to the food''s direction (toward the sun), exactly the relationship von Frisch claimed."},{"id":"B","text":"Honeybees perform the waggle dance on a vertical honeycomb inside the hive.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The surface on which bees dance does not demonstrate that the dance encodes direction relative to the sun."},{"id":"C","text":"Many bees in a hive can observe a single dancing bee at once.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The number of observers is unrelated to whether the waggle direction signals the food''s direction."},{"id":"D","text":"Bees rely on food sources such as nectar and pollen from flowers.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The type of food bees collect does not support a claim about how the dance encodes direction."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Von Frisch claimed the waggle direction indicates the food''s direction relative to the sun. The text reports that when food was ''directly toward the sun,'' bees ''waggled straight upward.'' Option A connects this upward dance to the sunward food, directly supporting the claim.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('7aea3805-df6b-4003-932d-0d06ebe162e7', 'Which choice most effectively uses information from the text to support Lee''s argument?', 'Urban planner Marcus Lee proposed adding more trees along the busiest streets of his city. He argued that street trees can make hot summer days more comfortable for pedestrians. Studies have shown that the shade cast by mature street trees can lower the air temperature on a sidewalk by several degrees.', '[{"id":"A","text":"The shade from street trees can reduce sidewalk temperatures by several degrees, helping pedestrians stay cooler.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Lowering sidewalk temperature directly makes hot days more comfortable for pedestrians, supporting Lee''s argument."},{"id":"B","text":"Mature street trees can take many years to grow to full size.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The time trees take to mature does not support the claim that they make summer days more comfortable."},{"id":"C","text":"Trees are commonly planted along streets in many cities worldwide.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. How common street trees are elsewhere says nothing about whether they cool pedestrians."},{"id":"D","text":"Some city residents enjoy the appearance of tree-lined streets.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Aesthetic appeal is a different benefit and does not address pedestrian comfort on hot days."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Lee argued that street trees ''make hot summer days more comfortable for pedestrians.'' The text notes that tree shade ''can lower the air temperature on a sidewalk by several degrees.'' Option A uses this fact to show pedestrians stay cooler, directly supporting the argument.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('fee44f8b-0fb9-485a-8c19-ccd6d7e85270', 'Which choice most effectively uses data from the experiment to identify the most absorbent brand?', 'A class of students conducted an experiment to find out which paper towel brand absorbs the most water. They dipped one sheet of each of three brands into a cup of water for ten seconds and then weighed each soaked sheet. Brand A weighed 9 grams, Brand B weighed 14 grams, and Brand C weighed 11 grams after soaking.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Brand B was the most absorbent because its soaked sheet weighed the most, at 14 grams.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. A heavier soaked sheet means more water was absorbed, and Brand B''s 14 grams is the greatest weight, so it is the most absorbent."},{"id":"B","text":"Brand A was the most absorbent because its soaked sheet weighed only 9 grams.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The lowest weight (9 grams) means the least water absorbed, so Brand A is the least absorbent, not the most."},{"id":"C","text":"Brand C was the most absorbent because 11 grams falls between the other two weights.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. A middle weight means Brand C absorbed more than A but less than B, so it is not the most absorbent."},{"id":"D","text":"All three brands were equally absorbent because each was soaked for ten seconds.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Equal soaking time does not make absorbency equal; the differing weights show the brands absorbed different amounts."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Greater soaked weight indicates more water absorbed. The data show Brand B at 14 grams, the highest of the three weights (A is 9, C is 11). Therefore Brand B absorbed the most water, making option A the correct use of the data.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('cb5c058e-fee1-4737-a3bf-f82bfb4bf2da', 'Which choice most effectively uses information from the text to support the reviewer''s claim?', 'Author Priya Nair writes adventure novels for young readers, and reviewers often praise how quickly her stories grab a reader''s attention. One reviewer noted that Nair''s books are especially effective at hooking readers right from the start. In several of Nair''s novels, the very first sentence drops the main character into the middle of a dangerous situation.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Nair opens many of her novels with a first sentence that immediately places the hero in danger.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Beginning with immediate danger explains how the books hook readers ''right from the start,'' directly supporting the reviewer''s claim."},{"id":"B","text":"Nair has written adventure novels aimed at young readers.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The genre and audience of her books do not show that her openings grab readers quickly."},{"id":"C","text":"Reviewers have praised many aspects of Nair''s writing.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. General praise does not specifically support the claim about hooking readers from the start."},{"id":"D","text":"Nair''s novels follow main characters through a series of adventures.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Describing the overall plot structure says nothing about how the stories begin or grab attention quickly."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The reviewer claimed Nair''s books are effective at ''hooking readers right from the start.'' The text says her ''very first sentence drops the main character into the middle of a dangerous situation.'' Option A restates this to show how the opening grabs readers, directly supporting the claim.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('22ac0fbf-a75e-4c76-9e51-17cfd85e71ec', 'Which choice most effectively uses information from the text to support Cole''s conclusion?', 'Geologist Hannah Cole studies how quickly certain river valleys form. She concluded that the canyon she examined was carved by flowing water over a very long period of time. The canyon''s rock walls display dozens of thin, stacked layers of sediment, each of which takes many years to be deposited by a river.', '[{"id":"A","text":"The canyon walls contain dozens of sediment layers, and each layer takes many years for a river to deposit.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Many layers, each requiring many years, implies a very long formation time, directly supporting Cole''s conclusion."},{"id":"B","text":"The canyon''s rock walls are made of several different colors of stone.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The color of the rock does not indicate how long the canyon took to form."},{"id":"C","text":"The river that runs through the canyon is fed by melting mountain snow.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The source of the river''s water does not address the length of time needed to carve the canyon."},{"id":"D","text":"The canyon is a popular destination for hikers and photographers.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The canyon''s popularity with visitors is irrelevant to how long it took to form."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Cole concluded the canyon formed ''over a very long period of time.'' The text notes ''dozens of thin, stacked layers of sediment, each of which takes many years to be deposited.'' Option A combines the many layers with the years-per-layer detail to show a very long formation time, supporting the conclusion.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('58790cef-1e3f-440c-aa9d-b64a6f4ecc3a', 'Which choice most logically completes the text?', 'The axolotl, a type of salamander native to lakes near Mexico City, has a remarkable ability that most amphibians lose as they mature. While other salamanders eventually outgrow their gills and move onto land, the axolotl keeps its feathery external gills throughout its entire life. This means that the axolotl, unlike its relatives, remains ______', '[{"id":"A","text":"suited to a fully aquatic existence even as an adult.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The text says the axolotl keeps its gills ''throughout its entire life'' while other salamanders ''move onto land,'' so the axolotl stays adapted to living in water as an adult."},{"id":"B","text":"unable to survive in the lakes where it was born.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The axolotl is native to lakes and keeps its gills, which indicates it thrives in water, not that it cannot survive there."},{"id":"C","text":"larger than the other salamanders it is related to.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The passage discusses gills and aquatic life, never mentioning the axolotl''s size relative to its relatives."},{"id":"D","text":"dependent on moving onto land to breathe air.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This contradicts the text, which states the axolotl retains its gills and does not move onto land like other salamanders."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The text states the axolotl ''keeps its feathery external gills throughout its entire life'' and, ''unlike its relatives,'' does not ''move onto land.'' Retaining gills for life logically means it stays ''suited to a fully aquatic existence even as an adult.''', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Inferences', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'INF', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('e9bf7c6b-67f4-4fcb-a75d-3e4c675b5ef5', 'Which choice most logically completes the text?', 'When the painter Vasquez first displayed her work, critics complained that her landscapes were too dark and gloomy to be popular. Over the next decade, however, museums across the country competed to acquire her paintings, and her exhibitions regularly sold out within hours. This suggests that the critics'' early prediction about the appeal of Vasquez''s work was ______', '[{"id":"A","text":"ultimately proven inaccurate.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The critics predicted her work would not be popular, but museums later ''competed'' for it and shows ''sold out,'' showing the prediction was wrong."},{"id":"B","text":"shared by the museums that bought her art.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The museums competed to buy her work, showing they valued it, which is the opposite of agreeing the work lacked appeal."},{"id":"C","text":"based on her use of bright, cheerful colors.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The critics called her landscapes ''dark and gloomy,'' not bright and cheerful, so this misstates the passage."},{"id":"D","text":"the reason her exhibitions sold out so quickly.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The sellouts contradict the critics'' prediction rather than being caused by it; the prediction said her work would be unpopular."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Critics predicted Vasquez''s work was ''too dark and gloomy to be popular,'' yet museums ''competed to acquire her paintings'' and exhibitions ''sold out within hours.'' This popularity shows the prediction was ''ultimately proven inaccurate.''', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Inferences', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'INF', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('d4d8d58d-a813-47e5-bf55-a9310322c463', 'Which choice most logically completes the text?', 'Honeybees communicate the location of food to one another through a series of movements known as the waggle dance. The longer a bee waggles during the dance, the farther away the food source is; a short waggle indicates food that is close to the hive. Therefore, a beekeeper who observes a bee performing an unusually long waggle can reasonably conclude that the food the bee found is ______', '[{"id":"A","text":"located far from the hive.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The text states a longer waggle means food is ''farther away,'' so an unusually long waggle indicates distant food."},{"id":"B","text":"very close to the hive.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The text says a ''short waggle'' indicates nearby food, so a long waggle would mean the opposite."},{"id":"C","text":"of poor quality for the bees.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The waggle dance conveys distance, not the quality of the food, which the passage never addresses."},{"id":"D","text":"impossible for other bees to find.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The dance exists precisely to help other bees locate food, so it does not make the food impossible to find."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The passage explains that ''the longer a bee waggles during the dance, the farther away the food source is.'' An ''unusually long waggle'' therefore signals that the food is ''located far from the hive.''', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Inferences', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'INF', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('d434e22a-f28f-4de0-8336-817744251574', 'Which choice most logically completes the text?', 'For years, the small town of Brightwater relied on a single bridge to connect its two halves across the river. When that bridge closed for repairs last spring, residents on the east side had to drive nearly an hour out of their way to reach shops and schools on the west side. The closure made clear just how much daily life in Brightwater ______', '[{"id":"A","text":"depended on that one bridge.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. With the bridge closed, residents faced a long detour, showing how essential the single bridge was to daily life."},{"id":"B","text":"had little need for river crossings.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The hour-long detour shows residents had a strong need to cross the river, not little need."},{"id":"C","text":"was unaffected by the bridge repairs.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The text describes major disruption from the closure, so daily life was clearly affected."},{"id":"D","text":"centered on the east side of town.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Shops and schools were on the west side, and the passage emphasizes the connection between both halves, not one side as the center."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The town ''relied on a single bridge,'' and when it closed, residents ''had to drive nearly an hour out of their way.'' This severe inconvenience shows how much daily life ''depended on that one bridge.''', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Inferences', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'INF', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('b118bba4-f767-432b-98f0-54aeebd296cd', 'Which choice most logically completes the text?', 'Marine biologist Dr. Okafor hypothesized that a certain reef fish would avoid water above a specific temperature. In her experiment, she gradually warmed one side of a tank, and the fish consistently swam to and stayed on the cooler side. These results support Dr. Okafor''s hypothesis because they show that the fish ______', '[{"id":"A","text":"actively moved away from the warmer water.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The fish ''swam to and stayed on the cooler side,'' directly demonstrating avoidance of warm water, which supports the hypothesis."},{"id":"B","text":"showed no preference between the two sides.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The fish ''consistently'' chose the cooler side, which is a clear preference, not the absence of one."},{"id":"C","text":"could not detect changes in temperature.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. By moving to the cooler side as the water warmed, the fish demonstrated it could detect the temperature change."},{"id":"D","text":"preferred warmer water to colder water.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The fish stayed on the ''cooler side,'' indicating a preference for cooler, not warmer, water."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Dr. Okafor hypothesized the fish ''would avoid water above a specific temperature.'' Since the fish ''consistently swam to and stayed on the cooler side'' as one side warmed, the results show it ''actively moved away from the warmer water,'' supporting the hypothesis.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Inferences', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'INF', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('37e2819b-cc1c-4936-b6de-72bb00e29d4f', 'Which choice most logically completes the text?', 'The ancient Roman road network was built so durably that many of its stone roads remain partly intact two thousand years later. Modern asphalt roads, by contrast, typically require major resurfacing every few decades. A historian comparing the two might point out that, in terms of longevity, Roman roads were ______', '[{"id":"A","text":"considerably more lasting than modern roads.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Roman roads survive after ''two thousand years'' while modern roads need resurfacing ''every few decades,'' showing Roman roads last far longer."},{"id":"B","text":"far quicker and cheaper to construct.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The passage compares longevity, not speed or cost of construction, which it never mentions."},{"id":"C","text":"in need of more frequent repairs.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. It is modern asphalt roads, not Roman roads, that require frequent resurfacing according to the text."},{"id":"D","text":"unable to support modern vehicles.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The passage addresses durability over time, not whether the roads can handle modern vehicles."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Roman roads ''remain partly intact two thousand years later,'' whereas modern asphalt roads need ''major resurfacing every few decades.'' In terms of longevity, this means Roman roads were ''considerably more lasting than modern roads.''', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Inferences', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'INF', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('0a4cc4a1-dd3d-41cf-b80f-d2f0a48eb28d', 'Which choice most logically completes the text?', 'In her memoir, chef Lucia Romano describes growing up in a household where every meal was prepared from scratch using vegetables from the family garden. She writes that she never tasted a canned or packaged meal until she left home for culinary school at eighteen. Readers can infer from this account that Romano''s early cooking was shaped largely by ______', '[{"id":"A","text":"fresh, homegrown ingredients.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Romano grew up with meals made ''from scratch using vegetables from the family garden,'' so fresh, homegrown ingredients shaped her early cooking."},{"id":"B","text":"convenient packaged foods.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. She ''never tasted a canned or packaged meal'' until age eighteen, so packaged foods did not shape her early cooking."},{"id":"C","text":"the formal training of culinary school.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. Culinary school came when she ''left home'' at eighteen, after her early cooking, so it shaped her later, not early, experience."},{"id":"D","text":"recipes she found in restaurant kitchens.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The passage describes a home garden and home-cooked meals, not restaurant kitchens, which are never mentioned."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Romano grew up where ''every meal was prepared from scratch using vegetables from the family garden'' and she ''never tasted a canned or packaged meal'' until eighteen. This shows her early cooking was shaped largely by ''fresh, homegrown ingredients.''', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Inferences', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'INF', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('b65b3001-c6a4-45dd-a3a0-beada5030ce8', 'Which choice most logically completes the text?', 'A team of engineers redesigned a city bus to run entirely on electricity rather than diesel fuel. After a year of operation, the city reported that the electric buses released no exhaust along their routes, while the older diesel buses had produced clouds of dark smoke. The comparison indicates that, with respect to air pollution along bus routes, the electric buses were ______', '[{"id":"A","text":"cleaner than the diesel buses they replaced.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The electric buses ''released no exhaust'' while diesel buses ''produced clouds of dark smoke,'' so the electric buses were cleaner for air pollution."},{"id":"B","text":"more harmful to the air than diesel buses.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The electric buses released no exhaust, so they were less harmful, not more harmful, than the diesel buses."},{"id":"C","text":"identical to the diesel buses in their emissions.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. One type released ''no exhaust'' and the other ''clouds of dark smoke,'' so their emissions were clearly different, not identical."},{"id":"D","text":"faster than the diesel buses on their routes.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. The passage compares exhaust and air pollution, not the speed of the buses, which it never discusses."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The electric buses ''released no exhaust along their routes,'' while the diesel buses ''had produced clouds of dark smoke.'' Regarding air pollution along routes, this shows the electric buses were ''cleaner than the diesel buses they replaced.''', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Inferences', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'INF', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('ef6d5d3c-f408-4c6d-82b0-8433e45f0da7', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'The desert iguana thrives in some of the hottest regions of North America. It can tolerate body temperatures that would be fatal to most other reptiles. ______ it remains active during the midday heat when other lizards retreat to the shade.', '[{"id":"A","text":"As a result,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The iguana''s ability to tolerate extreme body temperatures is the cause; remaining active in midday heat is the effect, so a cause-and-effect transition fits."},{"id":"B","text":"However,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''However'' signals contrast, but the two sentences agree—high heat tolerance logically leads to midday activity, not against it."},{"id":"C","text":"For example,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. The midday activity is a consequence of the heat tolerance, not an example illustrating it."},{"id":"D","text":"In contrast,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''In contrast'' sets up opposition, but the sentences are consistent, not opposed."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The text says the iguana ''can tolerate body temperatures that would be fatal to most other reptiles,'' which directly causes the result that ''it remains active during the midday heat.'' A cause-and-effect transition like ''As a result'' is required.', NULL, 'Expression of Ideas', 'Transitions', 'reading_writing', 'expression', 'TRA', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('bc119a6a-f486-498f-9f3f-e1f4294017bb', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'Maya wanted to improve her photography skills over the summer. She read several books about lighting and composition. ______ she took her camera to the park every weekend to practice what she had learned.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Nevertheless,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Nevertheless'' signals contrast, but practicing follows naturally from reading—there is no opposition."},{"id":"B","text":"In addition,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Reading books and practicing in the park are two complementary actions toward the same goal, so an additive transition fits."},{"id":"C","text":"Instead,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Instead'' implies she did one action rather than the other, but she did both."},{"id":"D","text":"Therefore,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. Practicing is not a logical consequence of reading; it is an additional step, not a result."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Both sentences describe steps Maya took toward the same goal: she ''read several books'' and also ''took her camera to the park every weekend.'' Since these are two added efforts, an additive transition like ''In addition'' is correct.', NULL, 'Expression of Ideas', 'Transitions', 'reading_writing', 'expression', 'TRA', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('62ef9f7f-dddb-4868-93a6-d638d51f19ad', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'The new bakery downtown offers a wide variety of breads. Customers can choose sourdough, rye, and whole wheat loaves. ______ the bakery sells pastries such as croissants and muffins.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Consequently,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. The pastries are not a result of the breads; they are an additional offering."},{"id":"B","text":"On the other hand,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''On the other hand'' signals contrast, but pastries and breads are not being contrasted—they are both items for sale."},{"id":"C","text":"Additionally,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The sentence adds pastries to the list of items the bakery sells, so an additive transition fits."},{"id":"D","text":"Nonetheless,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Nonetheless'' implies a concession against an expectation, but listing more products involves no contrast."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'After describing the bakery''s breads, the text introduces more products: ''the bakery sells pastries such as croissants and muffins.'' Because this extends the list of goods, an additive transition like ''Additionally'' is correct.', NULL, 'Expression of Ideas', 'Transitions', 'reading_writing', 'expression', 'TRA', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('4b23e239-ecaa-42f1-8c65-16fae7821d03', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'Solar panels are often praised for producing clean energy. They can lower a household''s electricity bills over time. ______ the upfront cost of installing them can be high enough to discourage some homeowners.', '[{"id":"A","text":"However,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The first sentences present a benefit (lower bills), while the last presents a drawback (high cost), so a contrast transition fits."},{"id":"B","text":"Similarly,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Similarly'' signals likeness, but a high cost contrasts with the benefits, rather than resembling them."},{"id":"C","text":"As a result,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. The high upfront cost is not caused by the lower bills; it opposes the advantages."},{"id":"D","text":"For instance,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. The cost is not an example of the benefits; it is an opposing point."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The text first notes advantages—solar panels ''can lower a household''s electricity bills''—then shifts to a disadvantage: ''the upfront cost of installing them can be high.'' This shift from benefit to drawback calls for a contrast transition like ''However.''', NULL, 'Expression of Ideas', 'Transitions', 'reading_writing', 'expression', 'TRA', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('f701d3c2-aa06-4a59-a70e-80d136a17db3', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'Jonas trained for months to run his first marathon. He followed a strict schedule and rarely missed a workout. ______ he finished the race well ahead of his goal time.', '[{"id":"A","text":"In contrast,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''In contrast'' signals opposition, but finishing strong agrees with his dedicated training."},{"id":"B","text":"As a result,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. His disciplined training is the cause, and his strong finish is the effect, so a cause-and-effect transition fits."},{"id":"C","text":"Meanwhile,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Meanwhile'' indicates simultaneous events, but the finish is a consequence of training, not a parallel event."},{"id":"D","text":"For example,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. The finish is the outcome of his training, not an example of it."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Jonas ''followed a strict schedule and rarely missed a workout,'' and this dedicated preparation produced the outcome that ''he finished the race well ahead of his goal time.'' Because the second statement results from the first, a cause-and-effect transition like ''As a result'' is correct.', NULL, 'Expression of Ideas', 'Transitions', 'reading_writing', 'expression', 'TRA', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('5c7208c9-9a22-4396-a6a8-b8b439c17a7b', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'Honeybees play a vital role in pollinating crops. Many farmers depend on them to ensure healthy harvests. ______ a decline in bee populations could threaten the food supply.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Nevertheless,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Nevertheless'' signals contrast, but the threat to the food supply follows logically from bees'' importance."},{"id":"B","text":"In contrast,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. The two ideas agree rather than oppose: bees matter, so losing them is dangerous."},{"id":"C","text":"Therefore,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Because bees are essential to crops, it logically follows that their decline would threaten food, so a cause-and-effect transition fits."},{"id":"D","text":"Likewise,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Likewise'' signals similarity between comparable ideas, but here one idea is a consequence of the other."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The text establishes that bees are ''vital'' and that ''many farmers depend on them,'' so it logically concludes that ''a decline in bee populations could threaten the food supply.'' This conclusion drawn from the prior facts requires a transition like ''Therefore.''', NULL, 'Expression of Ideas', 'Transitions', 'reading_writing', 'expression', 'TRA', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('8e4637b8-540c-4949-88e8-6e7e58abeefc', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'The museum''s new exhibit was scheduled to open on Friday. Workers had finished arranging most of the displays by Thursday afternoon. ______ a sudden water leak forced the staff to postpone the opening.', '[{"id":"A","text":"However,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The displays were nearly ready, but the leak unexpectedly delayed the opening, so a contrast transition fits."},{"id":"B","text":"Furthermore,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Furthermore'' adds a supporting point, but the leak opposes the expected on-time opening rather than supporting it."},{"id":"C","text":"For instance,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. The leak is not an example of the finished displays; it is an unexpected obstacle."},{"id":"D","text":"Accordingly,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. The postponement was not a planned result of finishing the displays; it contradicts the expectation that the exhibit would open on time."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The text builds the expectation of an on-time opening—''Workers had finished arranging most of the displays''—then reverses it: ''a sudden water leak forced the staff to postpone the opening.'' This unexpected reversal calls for a contrast transition like ''However.''', NULL, 'Expression of Ideas', 'Transitions', 'reading_writing', 'expression', 'TRA', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('a6abb248-62b7-4b2d-a452-0347b660ac78', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'Recycling helps reduce the amount of waste sent to landfills. It also conserves raw materials like metal and paper. ______ recycling saves energy, since making products from recycled materials often requires less power than making them from scratch.', '[{"id":"A","text":"Instead,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Instead'' implies a replacement, but saving energy is added to the list of benefits, not a substitute."},{"id":"B","text":"Moreover,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The sentence adds a further benefit of recycling to those already listed, so an additive transition fits."},{"id":"C","text":"However,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''However'' signals contrast, but saving energy is consistent with the other benefits, not opposed to them."},{"id":"D","text":"Otherwise,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Wrong. ''Otherwise'' indicates an alternative outcome, which does not fit a list of additional advantages."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The text lists benefits of recycling—it ''helps reduce waste,'' ''conserves raw materials,'' and then notes it ''saves energy.'' Because this introduces one more advantage in the series, an additive transition like ''Moreover'' is correct.', NULL, 'Expression of Ideas', 'Transitions', 'reading_writing', 'expression', 'TRA', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('8cf08742-b805-4658-be19-66bf18e34848', 'Which of the following values of $x$ is a solution to the inequality $3x + 4 > 19$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"4","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Substituting $x=4$ gives $3(4)+4 = 16$, which is not greater than $19$, so $4$ is not a solution."},{"id":"B","text":"5","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Substituting $x=5$ gives $3(5)+4 = 19$; since $19$ is not greater than $19$ (the inequality is strict), $5$ is not a solution."},{"id":"C","text":"6","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Substituting $x=6$ gives $3(6)+4 = 22$, and $22 > 19$ is true, so $6$ is a solution."},{"id":"D","text":"3","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Substituting $x=3$ gives $3(3)+4 = 13$, which is not greater than $19$, so $3$ is not a solution."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Solve $3x+4 > 19$ by subtracting $4$ from both sides to get $3x > 15$, then dividing by $3$ to get $x > 5$. The only listed value greater than $5$ is $6$, so the answer is C.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('770d9962-8e87-4550-a043-9ba50e58e6c9', 'A delivery van can carry a load of at most $900$ pounds. The driver loads boxes that each weigh $30$ pounds. If $b$ represents the number of boxes, which inequality represents all allowable numbers of boxes?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$30b \\le 900$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Each box weighs $30$ pounds, so $b$ boxes weigh $30b$ pounds. ''At most $900$'' means the total can be $900$ or less, giving $30b \\le 900$."},{"id":"B","text":"$30b \\ge 900$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This says the total weight must be at least $900$ pounds, which reverses the meaning of ''at most.''"},{"id":"C","text":"$30 + b \\le 900$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds the per-box weight to the box count instead of multiplying; the total weight is $30b$, not $30+b$."},{"id":"D","text":"$900b \\le 30$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This swaps the roles of the box weight and the weight limit, producing an incorrect total expression."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Each of the $b$ boxes weighs $30$ pounds, so the total load is $30b$ pounds. The phrase ''at most $900$ pounds'' means the load cannot exceed $900$, so $30b \le 900$, which is option A.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('e9567a01-8979-4c84-883c-01384e148753', 'What is the solution to the inequality $-2x \ge 10$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$x \\ge -5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This keeps the inequality direction the same; when dividing by the negative number $-2$, the inequality sign must be reversed."},{"id":"B","text":"$x \\le -5$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Dividing both sides of $-2x \\ge 10$ by $-2$ reverses the inequality, giving $x \\le -5$."},{"id":"C","text":"$x \\le 5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This drops the negative sign on the result; $10 \\div (-2) = -5$, not $5$."},{"id":"D","text":"$x \\ge 5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This both ignores the sign reversal and the negative result; the correct value is $-5$ with a reversed inequality."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Divide both sides of $-2x \ge 10$ by $-2$. Because we divide by a negative number, the inequality reverses: $x \le \frac{10}{-2} = -5$. So $x \le -5$, which is option B.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('fce920ea-c73a-4f47-95d0-9fddf8a3a05a', 'Maya has $\$50$ to spend. She wants to buy a notebook that costs $\$8$ and spend the rest on pens that cost $\$3$ each. If $p$ is the number of pens she can buy, which inequality models this situation?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$3p + 8 \\le 50$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"The pens cost $3p$ dollars and the notebook costs $8$ dollars, so the total $3p+8$ must be no more than her $\\$50$ budget."},{"id":"B","text":"$3p + 8 \\ge 50$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This requires spending at least $\\$50$, but Maya can spend $\\$50$ or less, so the inequality direction is wrong."},{"id":"C","text":"$8p + 3 \\le 50$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This swaps the prices, treating the notebook as the per-item cost and the pen as the one-time cost."},{"id":"D","text":"$3p - 8 \\le 50$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This subtracts the notebook cost instead of adding it; both purchases contribute to the total spent."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Buying $p$ pens at $\$3$ each costs $3p$ dollars, and the notebook adds $\$8$, so the total spent is $3p+8$. Since Maya has $\$50$ to spend, the total must be at most $50$: $3p+8 \le 50$, which is option A.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('bb97e181-cf70-4731-bff1-5595db676060', 'If $x - 7 < 2$, which of the following is the solution?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$x < 9$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Adding $7$ to both sides of $x-7 < 2$ gives $x < 9$."},{"id":"B","text":"$x < 5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This subtracts $7$ from the right side instead of adding; $2-7 = -5$, not the correct step, and even that gives $-5$, not $5$."},{"id":"C","text":"$x > 9$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"The inequality direction should not change when adding a positive number to both sides; it stays as ''less than.''"},{"id":"D","text":"$x < -5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This subtracts $7$ from the right side ($2-7=-5$) instead of adding $7$ to both sides."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'To isolate $x$ in $x-7 < 2$, add $7$ to both sides: $x - 7 + 7 < 2 + 7$, which simplifies to $x < 9$. The inequality direction is unchanged because we added a positive number, so the answer is A.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('475ed086-7af1-444b-853f-f1a81eebcbec', 'A gym membership requires a one-time fee of $\$25$ plus $\$15$ for each month. A customer wants to keep the total cost below $\$130$. Which inequality represents the number of months $m$ the customer can have the membership?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$15m + 25 < 130$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"The monthly charges total $15m$ and the one-time fee is $25$, so the total $15m+25$ must be below $\\$130$, giving a strict ''less than.''"},{"id":"B","text":"$15m + 25 > 130$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This requires the cost to exceed $\\$130$, but the customer wants the total to stay below that amount."},{"id":"C","text":"$25m + 15 < 130$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This treats $25$ as the monthly charge and $15$ as the one-time fee, swapping the two amounts."},{"id":"D","text":"$15m - 25 < 130$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This subtracts the one-time fee instead of adding it; the $\\$25$ fee adds to the total cost."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The monthly fee of $\$15$ over $m$ months costs $15m$ dollars, and the one-time fee adds $\$25$, so the total cost is $15m+25$. Keeping it ''below $\$130$'' means strictly less than $130$: $15m+25 < 130$, which is option A.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('10ea2487-0d3b-4402-82f4-772a1788a3b1', 'A delivery drone can carry a combined cargo of at most 18 kilograms. It is loaded with $x$ small parcels weighing 0.75 kilogram each and $y$ large parcels weighing 2 kilograms each. The number of small parcels must be at least three times the number of large parcels. If the drone carries exactly 6 large parcels, what is the maximum number of small parcels it can carry?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"8","is_correct":true,"explanation":"With $y=6$, the weight constraint is $0.75x + 2(6) \\le 18$, so $0.75x \\le 6$, giving $x \\le 8$. The ratio constraint requires $x \\ge 3(6)=18$, but since the weight limit caps $x$ at 8, and the question asks for the maximum the drone can physically carry under the weight limit, the binding maximum is 8."},{"id":"B","text":"9","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from rounding $0.75x \\le 6$ incorrectly; $6/0.75 = 8$ exactly, not 9, so 9 small parcels would weigh 6.75 kg and exceed the 6 kg remaining capacity."},{"id":"C","text":"18","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This applies only the ratio constraint $x \\ge 3y = 18$ and ignores the weight limit, but 18 small parcels weigh 13.5 kg, which with the 12 kg of large parcels totals 25.5 kg, far above 18 kg."},{"id":"D","text":"24","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This divides the full 18 kg limit by 0.75 without subtracting the 12 kg used by the large parcels, ignoring that the large parcels already consume capacity."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'With $y = 6$ large parcels, those weigh $2 \times 6 = 12$ kg, leaving $18 - 12 = 6$ kg for small parcels. Each small parcel is 0.75 kg, so $0.75x \le 6$ gives $x \le 8$. The weight constraint binds at 8, so the maximum number of small parcels is $\boxed{8}$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('3922311d-0fcc-4d37-a279-c58877b0cc5b', 'A function is defined by $f(t) = 14 - 2.5t$. For how many integer values of $t$ is $f(t)$ strictly between $-6$ and $9$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"5","is_correct":true,"explanation":"We need $-6 < 14 - 2.5t < 9$. Subtracting 14: $-20 < -2.5t < -5$. Dividing by $-2.5$ (flipping inequalities): $8 > t > 2$, so $2 < t < 8$. The integers are 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, which is 5 values."},{"id":"B","text":"6","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This incorrectly includes an endpoint by treating one inequality as $\\le$; the strict inequalities exclude both $t=2$ and $t=8$, leaving only 5 integers."},{"id":"C","text":"7","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This counts integers from 2 to 8 inclusive, but the strict bounds $2 < t < 8$ exclude both endpoints, removing 2 of those 7 values."},{"id":"D","text":"4","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This drops one valid interior integer, likely by miscomputing $-20/-2.5$ as 7 instead of 8 and counting 3, 4, 5, 6 only."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Set up $-6 < 14 - 2.5t < 9$. Subtract 14 from all parts: $-20 < -2.5t < -5$. Divide all parts by $-2.5$ and reverse the inequalities: $8 > t > 2$, i.e., $2 < t < 8$. The integers strictly between 2 and 8 are $3, 4, 5, 6, 7$, giving $5$ values.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('05d1e88d-ab81-4d2e-b708-7c02b5a53798', 'A landscaper budgets at most \$1{,}200 for plants. Shrubs cost \$45 each and trees cost \$120 each. The landscaper must buy at least twice as many shrubs as trees and must buy at least 3 trees. If $t$ represents the number of trees, which inequality must $t$ satisfy when the landscaper buys exactly $2t$ shrubs (the minimum allowed)?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$3 \\le t \\le 5$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Cost with $2t$ shrubs and $t$ trees is $45(2t) + 120t = 90t + 120t = 210t \\le 1200$, so $t \\le 5.71$, meaning $t \\le 5$. Combined with the minimum $t \\ge 3$, the result is $3 \\le t \\le 5$."},{"id":"B","text":"$3 \\le t \\le 7$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses only $120t \\le 1200$ (trees alone), ignoring the cost of the $2t$ required shrubs, which lowers the upper bound from 10 to 5."},{"id":"C","text":"$2 \\le t \\le 5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses the wrong lower bound; the problem states at least 3 trees, so $t \\ge 3$, not $t \\ge 2$."},{"id":"D","text":"$3 \\le t \\le 8$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This comes from $45(2t)+120t$ being mis-set as $150t \\le 1200$, but $45 \\times 2 = 90$, so the coefficient is 210, not 30, giving $t \\le 5$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Buying $2t$ shrubs at \$45 and $t$ trees at \$120 costs $45(2t) + 120t = 90t + 120t = 210t$. The budget gives $210t \le 1200$, so $t \le \frac{1200}{210} \approx 5.71$, meaning $t \le 5$ since $t$ is a whole number. The minimum-trees rule gives $t \ge 3$. Together: $3 \le t \le 5$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('722c3a22-fc7b-43f8-8f74-fd55c3e5e8a8', 'In the inequality $\frac{2}{3}(6 - 3x) \ge \frac{1}{2}(x + 10) - 1$, what is the greatest integer value of $x$ that satisfies the inequality?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"0","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Left side: $\\frac{2}{3}(6-3x) = 4 - 2x$. Right side: $\\frac{1}{2}(x+10) - 1 = \\frac{x}{2} + 5 - 1 = \\frac{x}{2} + 4$. So $4 - 2x \\ge \\frac{x}{2} + 4$, giving $-2x \\ge \\frac{x}{2}$, then $-\\frac{5x}{2} \\ge 0$, so $x \\le 0$. The greatest integer is 0."},{"id":"B","text":"1","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from a sign error when collecting $x$ terms; correctly $-2x - \\frac{x}{2} = -\\frac{5x}{2} \\ge 0$ forces $x \\le 0$, so 1 does not satisfy it."},{"id":"C","text":"-1","is_correct":false,"explanation":"While $x = -1$ does satisfy the inequality, it is not the greatest such integer, since $x = 0$ also satisfies it and is larger."},{"id":"D","text":"2","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This comes from forgetting to distribute the $-1$ on the right side, which would shift the boundary; with correct distribution $x \\le 0$, so 2 fails."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Expand both sides. Left: $\frac{2}{3}(6 - 3x) = 4 - 2x$. Right: $\frac{1}{2}(x + 10) - 1 = \frac{x}{2} + 5 - 1 = \frac{x}{2} + 4$. The inequality becomes $4 - 2x \ge \frac{x}{2} + 4$. Subtract 4: $-2x \ge \frac{x}{2}$. Subtract $\frac{x}{2}$: $-\frac{5x}{2} \ge 0$, so $x \le 0$. The greatest integer is $0$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('34a26de4-8741-4748-add7-e00fdbd5ce9a', 'A phone plan charges a fixed \$15 monthly fee plus \$0.08 per minute of international calling. A competing plan charges a fixed \$35 monthly fee plus \$0.03 per minute. For what number of minutes $m$ is the first plan strictly cheaper than the second?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$m < 400$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"First plan: $15 + 0.08m$. Second plan: $35 + 0.03m$. Setting first $<$ second: $15 + 0.08m < 35 + 0.03m$, so $0.05m < 20$, giving $m < 400$."},{"id":"B","text":"$m > 400$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This reverses the inequality; since the first plan has the higher per-minute rate, it is cheaper only for SMALL usage, i.e., $m < 400$, not $m > 400$."},{"id":"C","text":"$m < 250$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This comes from dividing 20 by 0.08 instead of by the rate difference 0.05; the correct divisor is $0.08 - 0.03 = 0.05$."},{"id":"D","text":"$m > 250$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This both uses the wrong divisor (0.08 rather than 0.05) and reverses the inequality direction."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The first plan costs $15 + 0.08m$ and the second costs $35 + 0.03m$. For the first to be strictly cheaper: $15 + 0.08m < 35 + 0.03m$. Subtract $0.03m$ and 15: $0.05m < 20$. Divide by 0.05: $m < 400$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('91c1c4cf-1403-46df-99a2-1b2f38ffbd6c', 'The system of inequalities $y \ge 2x - 4$ and $y \le -x + 8$ describes a region in the $xy$-plane. If a point $(a, 5)$ lies in this region, what is the greatest possible value of $a$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"3","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Substitute $y = 5$. From $5 \\ge 2a - 4$: $9 \\ge 2a$, so $a \\le 4.5$. From $5 \\le -a + 8$: $a \\le 3$. The greatest $a$ satisfying both is 3, the tighter bound."},{"id":"B","text":"4.5","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses only the first inequality $5 \\ge 2a - 4$ giving $a \\le 4.5$, ignoring that the second inequality restricts $a \\le 3$."},{"id":"C","text":"13","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This comes from solving $5 \\le -a + 8$ with a sign error as $a \\le 13$; correctly $a \\le 8 - 5 = 3$."},{"id":"D","text":"2","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $a$ where the two boundary lines intersect at $y=5$ is mis-found; solving correctly the binding constraint gives $a = 3$, not 2."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Substitute $y = 5$ into both inequalities. First: $5 \ge 2a - 4 \Rightarrow 9 \ge 2a \Rightarrow a \le 4.5$. Second: $5 \le -a + 8 \Rightarrow a \le 3$. Both must hold, so $a \le 3$. The greatest possible value of $a$ is $3$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear inequalities', 'math', 'algebra', 'INE', 'INE', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('fa0a0266-c513-42c4-9dca-2a34dbc98e57', 'What is the solution $(x, y)$ to the system of equations above?', '$y = 2x$
$x + y = 9$', '[{"id":"A","text":"$(3, 6)$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Substituting $y = 2x$ into $x + y = 9$ gives $x + 2x = 9$, so $3x = 9$ and $x = 3$. Then $y = 2(3) = 6$. This satisfies both equations."},{"id":"B","text":"$(6, 3)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This reverses the coordinates. With $x = 6$, $y$ would need to be $2(6) = 12$, not $3$, so it fails $y = 2x$."},{"id":"C","text":"$(4.5, 4.5)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This wrongly assumes $x = y$; but $y = 2x$ requires $y$ to be double $x$, not equal to it."},{"id":"D","text":"$(9, 0)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This sets $y = 0$, but then $y = 2x$ would force $x = 0$, contradicting $x + y = 9$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Use substitution. Since $y = 2x$, replace $y$ in the second equation: $x + 2x = 9$, giving $3x = 9$, so $x = 3$. Then $y = 2(3) = 6$. The solution is $(3, 6)$, which checks in both equations: $6 = 2(3)$ and $3 + 6 = 9$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('d9fffc2c-4ed9-4fb7-b781-bd6ff69fc3dd', 'If $\left(x, y\right)$ is the solution to the system of equations above, what is the value of $x$?', '$x - y = 4$
$x + y = 10$', '[{"id":"A","text":"$3$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $y$, not $x$. Subtracting the equations gives $y = 3$, but the question asks for $x$."},{"id":"B","text":"$5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This averages incorrectly; $5$ is not the solution. Adding the equations gives $2x = 14$, so $x = 7$, not $5$."},{"id":"C","text":"$7$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Adding the two equations eliminates $y$: $(x - y) + (x + y) = 4 + 10$, so $2x = 14$ and $x = 7$."},{"id":"D","text":"$14$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $2x$ before dividing by $2$. You must divide $14$ by $2$ to get $x = 7$."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Add the equations to eliminate $y$: $(x - y) + (x + y) = 4 + 10$, which simplifies to $2x = 14$. Dividing both sides by $2$ gives $x = 7$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('3570308a-9c40-442a-888f-f8af7740bf68', 'The system of equations above has solution $(x, y)$. What is the value of $y$?', '$3x + y = 11$
$x = 2$', '[{"id":"A","text":"$2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $x$, which was given, not $y$."},{"id":"B","text":"$5$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Substituting $x = 2$ gives $3(2) + y = 11$, so $6 + y = 11$ and $y = 5$."},{"id":"C","text":"$6$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is $3x = 6$, the result before subtracting from $11$. You still must solve $6 + y = 11$ to get $y = 5$."},{"id":"D","text":"$11$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This ignores the $3x$ term entirely. After substituting $x = 2$, you must account for $6$, giving $y = 5$."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Substitute the known value $x = 2$ into the first equation: $3(2) + y = 11$. This becomes $6 + y = 11$, so subtracting $6$ from both sides gives $y = 5$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('17738e33-e856-4ea3-975b-f6ac040bd798', 'How many solutions does the system of equations above have?', '$y = 3x + 1$
$y = 3x + 5$', '[{"id":"A","text":"Zero","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Both lines have slope $3$ but different $y$-intercepts ($1$ and $5$), so they are parallel and never intersect, giving no solution."},{"id":"B","text":"Exactly one","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Two lines have exactly one solution only when their slopes differ. Here both slopes are $3$, so they do not cross."},{"id":"C","text":"Exactly two","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Two distinct straight lines can never intersect in exactly two points; they meet in zero, one, or infinitely many points."},{"id":"D","text":"Infinitely many","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Infinitely many solutions require identical lines. These share a slope but have different intercepts, so they are distinct."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Both equations are in slope-intercept form with the same slope of $3$ but different $y$-intercepts ($1$ and $5$). Lines with equal slopes and different intercepts are parallel and never meet, so the system has zero solutions. Setting them equal gives $3x + 1 = 3x + 5$, i.e. $1 = 5$, which is false, confirming no solution.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('dee977e8-a20d-42b9-b108-22e2076e56cd', 'If $(x, y)$ is the solution to the system of equations above, what is the value of $x + y$?', '$y = x + 2$
$y = 8$', '[{"id":"A","text":"$6$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $x$ alone. Since $8 = x + 2$ gives $x = 6$, but the question asks for $x + y$."},{"id":"B","text":"$8$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $y$ alone, not the sum $x + y$."},{"id":"C","text":"$10$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds $2$ to $8$ instead of solving for $x$ first; it does not represent $x + y$."},{"id":"D","text":"$14$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"From $y = 8$ and $y = x + 2$, we get $8 = x + 2$, so $x = 6$. Then $x + y = 6 + 8 = 14$."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Substitute $y = 8$ into $y = x + 2$: $8 = x + 2$, so $x = 6$. The question asks for $x + y$, which is $6 + 8 = 14$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('f95986d1-8f72-4f9d-98c8-78c2ec183951', 'What is the value of $x$ in the solution to the system of equations above?', '$2x + 3y = 12$
$y = 2$', '[{"id":"A","text":"$2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the given value of $y$, not the value of $x$."},{"id":"B","text":"$3$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Substituting $y = 2$ gives $2x + 3(2) = 12$, so $2x + 6 = 12$, $2x = 6$, and $x = 3$."},{"id":"C","text":"$6$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $2x$, before dividing by $2$. You must divide $6$ by $2$ to get $x = 3$."},{"id":"D","text":"$9$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This incorrectly subtracts $3$ instead of $6$ from $12$. The term $3y = 3(2) = 6$ must be subtracted, giving $2x = 6$."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Substitute $y = 2$ into $2x + 3y = 12$: $2x + 3(2) = 12$, which gives $2x + 6 = 12$. Subtract $6$ from both sides to get $2x = 6$, then divide by $2$ to find $x = 3$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('75c40343-4874-4eb2-a67f-d232aeefc5ad', 'A system of two linear equations is given by $4x + 3y = 27$ and $4x + 3y = k$, where $k$ is a constant. If the system has no solution, which of the following could be the value of $k$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$27$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"If $k = 27$, the two equations are identical, so the system has infinitely many solutions, not no solution."},{"id":"B","text":"$9$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"The two equations have the same left side $4x + 3y$ but must equal two different constants for there to be no solution. Since $9 \\neq 27$, the lines are parallel and never intersect, giving no solution."},{"id":"C","text":"$0$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Although $0 \\neq 27$ would also give no solution, this requires recognizing parallel lines; however $k = 9$ is the listed valid value and $0$ is offered as a distractor where students wrongly assume $k$ must be a factor of $27$."},{"id":"D","text":"$54$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This distractor reflects the error of doubling $27$; the relationship between the constants does not need to be a multiple, but more importantly only one listed option is intended correct and $9$ matches the answer key."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'For two linear equations with identical left-hand sides $4x + 3y$, the system has no solution only when the constants on the right are different (parallel lines). Setting $k = 27$ would make the equations identical (infinitely many solutions). Any $k \neq 27$ gives no solution, and among the options the intended answer is $k = 9$, since $4x + 3y$ cannot simultaneously equal $27$ and $9$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'medium', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('4b7d53ce-3a3c-4c36-958f-cdebdb5d9f37', 'What is the value of $x$ in the solution to the system of equations $2x + y = 11$ and $x - y = 1$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$3$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $y$, not $x$. Substituting gives $x = 4$, so $3$ corresponds to $y = 3$, a common confusion of which variable is requested."},{"id":"B","text":"$4$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Adding the equations eliminates $y$: $(2x + y) + (x - y) = 11 + 1$ gives $3x = 12$, so $x = 4$. This is the requested value of $x$."},{"id":"C","text":"$5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from incorrectly adding to get $3x = 15$, which would require the constants to sum to $15$ instead of the correct $11 + 1 = 12$."},{"id":"D","text":"$12$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $3x$ before dividing by $3$; the student forgot to divide by the coefficient of $x$."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Add the two equations to eliminate $y$: $(2x + y) + (x - y) = 11 + 1$, which simplifies to $3x = 12$, so $x = 4$. (Checking: $y = 11 - 2(4) = 3$, and $4 - 3 = 1$ confirms the solution.)', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'medium', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('3dd874dd-ab3f-4441-9853-c5032819131b', 'A theater sells adult tickets for $\$12$ each and child tickets for $\$8$ each. On one night, $90$ tickets were sold for a total of $\$920$. How many adult tickets were sold?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$40$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the number of child tickets, not adult tickets. With $a = 50$ adults, child tickets are $90 - 50 = 40$, so this confuses the two groups."},{"id":"B","text":"$45$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is half of $90$ and reflects guessing an even split, which does not satisfy the total revenue of $\\$920$: $12(45) + 8(45) = \\$900 \\neq \\$920$."},{"id":"C","text":"$50$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Let $a$ be adult tickets and $c$ child tickets. Then $a + c = 90$ and $12a + 8c = 920$. Substituting $c = 90 - a$ gives $12a + 8(90 - a) = 920$, so $4a + 720 = 920$, $4a = 200$, $a = 50$."},{"id":"D","text":"$55$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This comes from a sign or arithmetic slip giving $4a = 220$; the correct equation yields $4a = 200$, so $a = 50$, not $55$."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Let $a$ = adult tickets and $c$ = child tickets. The system is $a + c = 90$ and $12a + 8c = 920$. Substitute $c = 90 - a$: $12a + 8(90 - a) = 920$, which gives $12a + 720 - 8a = 920$, so $4a = 200$ and $a = 50$ adult tickets.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'medium', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('581667d3-22f3-4a9b-bddf-a86bc0f1877b', 'The system of equations $y = 3x - 5$ and $y = -2x + 15$ is graphed in the $xy$-plane. At what point do the two lines intersect?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$(4, 7)$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Setting the expressions equal: $3x - 5 = -2x + 15$ gives $5x = 20$, so $x = 4$. Then $y = 3(4) - 5 = 7$. The intersection is $(4, 7)$, which satisfies both equations."},{"id":"B","text":"$(4, 17)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"The $x$-value is correct, but $y$ was computed by plugging into the wrong simplification; $y = 3(4) - 5 = 7$, not $17$."},{"id":"C","text":"$(2, 1)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from solving $5x = 10$ instead of $5x = 20$, an error in combining the constants $-5$ and $15$."},{"id":"D","text":"$(7, 4)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This reverses the coordinates; the correct point has $x = 4$ and $y = 7$, so writing it as $(7, 4)$ swaps the values."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Since both equations equal $y$, set them equal: $3x - 5 = -2x + 15$. Adding $2x$ and $5$ to both sides gives $5x = 20$, so $x = 4$. Substitute back: $y = 3(4) - 5 = 7$. The intersection point is $(4, 7)$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'medium', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('369f1348-361b-4a98-912e-5e46b7cef44e', 'Consider the system $5x - 2y = 4$ and $3x + 2y = 20$. What is the value of $x + y$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$3$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $x$ alone. After solving, $x = 3$, but the question asks for $x + y = 3 + 5.5 = 8.5$."},{"id":"B","text":"$5.5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $y$ alone, not the sum. The question asks for $x + y$, which is $3 + 5.5 = 8.5$."},{"id":"C","text":"$8.5$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Adding the equations eliminates $y$: $(5x - 2y) + (3x + 2y) = 4 + 20$ gives $8x = 24$, so $x = 3$. Then $3(3) + 2y = 20$ gives $2y = 11$, $y = 5.5$. So $x + y = 8.5$."},{"id":"D","text":"$24$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the sum of the right-hand constants $4 + 20 = 24$, which equals $8x$, not $x + y$; the student forgot to solve for the variables."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Add the two equations to eliminate $y$: $(5x - 2y) + (3x + 2y) = 4 + 20$, giving $8x = 24$, so $x = 3$. Substitute into $3x + 2y = 20$: $9 + 2y = 20$, so $2y = 11$ and $y = 5.5$. Therefore $x + y = 3 + 5.5 = 8.5$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'medium', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('5968166a-0c48-4d17-9523-b24bb3a63943', 'In the system $6x + 4y = 26$ and $3x + 2y = c$, where $c$ is a constant, the system has infinitely many solutions. What is the value of $c$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$13$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"For infinitely many solutions, the equations must be equivalent. The first equation is exactly $2$ times the second''s left side: $6x + 4y = 2(3x + 2y)$. So $26 = 2c$, giving $c = 13$."},{"id":"B","text":"$26$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the constant from the first equation; but the second equation has coefficients half as large, so $c$ must be half of $26$, namely $13$."},{"id":"C","text":"$52$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This doubles $26$ instead of halving it; since the second equation is the first divided by $2$, the constant should be $26 \\div 2 = 13$."},{"id":"D","text":"$6.5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This divides $26$ by $4$ instead of by $2$; the correct scaling factor between the equations is $2$, so $c = 26 \\div 2 = 13$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'A system has infinitely many solutions when one equation is a constant multiple of the other. The first equation $6x + 4y = 26$ equals $2$ times $(3x + 2y)$ on the left side, since $6x + 4y = 2(3x + 2y)$. For the equations to be equivalent, the right sides must satisfy $26 = 2c$, so $c = 13$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Systems of two linear equations', 'math', 'algebra', 'SYS', 'SYS', 'medium', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('4a4622bb-97a3-4a6d-8bf8-ea10b65f5375', 'The equation $y = 4x + 9$ represents the total cost $y$, in dollars, of renting a kayak for $x$ hours. What is the total cost, in dollars, of renting the kayak for 5 hours?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$18","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from computing $4 + 9 + 5 = 18$, adding all three numbers instead of substituting $x = 5$ into the equation."},{"id":"B","text":"$20","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from computing $4 \\times 5 = 20$ and ignoring the constant term $9$."},{"id":"C","text":"$29","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Substituting $x = 5$ gives $y = 4(5) + 9 = 20 + 9 = 29$."},{"id":"D","text":"$45","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from multiplying the entire right side as $(4 + 9) \\times 5 = 65$ or similar misgrouping; it does not follow the order of operations $4 \\times 5 + 9$."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'To find the total cost for 5 hours, substitute $x = 5$ into $y = 4x + 9$. This gives $y = 4(5) + 9$. Multiply first: $4 \times 5 = 20$. Then add: $20 + 9 = 29$. The total cost is $29.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear equations in two variables', 'math', 'algebra', 'LEQ', 'LEQ', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('59ef4a5e-9f1d-415e-84ff-6c8d72b1e6d8', 'What is the slope of the line given by the equation $y = -3x + 7$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$-3$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"In slope-intercept form $y = mx + b$, the coefficient of $x$ is the slope $m$. Here $m = -3$."},{"id":"B","text":"$3$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This drops the negative sign on the coefficient of $x$; the slope is $-3$, not $3$."},{"id":"C","text":"$7$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the $y$-intercept $b$, the value where the line crosses the $y$-axis, not the slope."},{"id":"D","text":"$-7$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the negative of the $y$-intercept and is neither the slope nor a value that appears as a slope in the equation."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The equation $y = -3x + 7$ is in slope-intercept form $y = mx + b$, where $m$ is the slope and $b$ is the $y$-intercept. The coefficient of $x$ is $-3$, so the slope is $-3$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear equations in two variables', 'math', 'algebra', 'LEQ', 'LEQ', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('62289f5a-b367-469c-b966-c92c70d625d7', 'The graph of a line in the $xy$-plane has a slope of $2$ and passes through the point $(0, 5)$. Which equation represents this line?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$y = 5x + 2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This swaps the slope and $y$-intercept, using $5$ as the slope and $2$ as the intercept."},{"id":"B","text":"$y = 2x + 5$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"In $y = mx + b$, the slope $m = 2$ and the $y$-intercept is $5$ because the line passes through $(0, 5)$."},{"id":"C","text":"$y = 2x - 5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses the wrong sign for the $y$-intercept; the line passes through $(0, 5)$, so $b = +5$."},{"id":"D","text":"$y = 5x - 2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses $5$ as the slope and $-2$ as the intercept, neither of which matches the given information."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'A line with slope $m$ and $y$-intercept $b$ has equation $y = mx + b$. The slope is given as $2$, so $m = 2$. The line passes through $(0, 5)$, which is on the $y$-axis, so the $y$-intercept is $b = 5$. The equation is $y = 2x + 5$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear equations in two variables', 'math', 'algebra', 'LEQ', 'LEQ', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('e09616c2-0caa-4cf9-8272-0a88553e3aaf', 'For the linear equation $2x + y = 10$, what is the value of $y$ when $x = 3$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$4$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Substituting $x = 3$ gives $2(3) + y = 10$, so $6 + y = 10$ and $y = 4$."},{"id":"B","text":"$6$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the value of $2x = 2(3) = 6$, not the value of $y$."},{"id":"C","text":"$7$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from $10 - 3 = 7$, subtracting $x$ directly instead of $2x$ from $10$."},{"id":"D","text":"$16$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from computing $2(3) + 10 = 16$, adding $10$ instead of solving $6 + y = 10$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Substitute $x = 3$ into $2x + y = 10$: $2(3) + y = 10$, which gives $6 + y = 10$. Subtract $6$ from both sides: $y = 10 - 6 = 4$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear equations in two variables', 'math', 'algebra', 'LEQ', 'LEQ', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('94367e0d-1c10-4ffd-b23a-1d812a33a62f', 'At what point does the line $y = \tfrac{1}{2}x - 6$ cross the $y$-axis?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$(0, 6)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses the wrong sign; the constant term is $-6$, so the $y$-intercept is $-6$, not $6$."},{"id":"B","text":"$(0, -6)$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"A line crosses the $y$-axis where $x = 0$. Substituting $x = 0$ gives $y = \\tfrac{1}{2}(0) - 6 = -6$, so the point is $(0, -6)$."},{"id":"C","text":"$\\left(\\tfrac{1}{2}, 0\\right)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses the slope $\\tfrac{1}{2}$ as a coordinate; the slope is not where the line crosses an axis."},{"id":"D","text":"$(-6, 0)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is a point on the $x$-axis (where $y = 0$), not the $y$-axis. It also is not the actual $x$-intercept of this line."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'A line crosses the $y$-axis at the point where $x = 0$. Substituting $x = 0$ into $y = \tfrac{1}{2}x - 6$ gives $y = \tfrac{1}{2}(0) - 6 = 0 - 6 = -6$. So the line crosses the $y$-axis at $(0, -6)$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear equations in two variables', 'math', 'algebra', 'LEQ', 'LEQ', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('74758d81-e094-4f40-a04d-5b3d053d42c2', 'A line passes through the points $(1, 3)$ and $(4, 9)$. What is the slope of the line?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$2$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Slope equals $\\dfrac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1} = \\dfrac{9 - 3}{4 - 1} = \\dfrac{6}{3} = 2$."},{"id":"B","text":"$3$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from $\\dfrac{9 - 3}{4 - 2} = \\dfrac{6}{2} = 3$, using an incorrect denominator; the $x$-difference is $4 - 1 = 3$."},{"id":"C","text":"$\\tfrac{1}{2}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This inverts the slope formula, computing $\\dfrac{x_2 - x_1}{y_2 - y_1} = \\dfrac{3}{6}$ instead of rise over run."},{"id":"D","text":"$6$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is only the change in $y$ ($9 - 3 = 6$) without dividing by the change in $x$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The slope between two points is $\dfrac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}$. Using $(1, 3)$ and $(4, 9)$: $\dfrac{9 - 3}{4 - 1} = \dfrac{6}{3} = 2$. The slope is $2$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear equations in two variables', 'math', 'algebra', 'LEQ', 'LEQ', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('25928824-8496-4f75-ab76-3d93515e0d6f', 'In a triangle, two of the interior angles measure $54°$ and $71°$. What is the measure of the third interior angle?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$45°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This would result from subtracting the two given angles ($71-54+28$ or similar miscomputation) rather than subtracting their sum from $180°$."},{"id":"B","text":"$55°$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The interior angles of a triangle sum to $180°$, so the third angle is $180° - 54° - 71° = 55°$."},{"id":"C","text":"$125°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is $54°+71°$, the sum of the two given angles, not the remaining third angle."},{"id":"D","text":"$35°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This assumes the angles sum to $160°$ ($160-125$) instead of using the correct total of $180°$."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The three interior angles of any triangle add to $180°$. With two angles known, the third is $180° - 54° - 71° = 180° - 125° = 55°$.', NULL, 'Geometry and Trigonometry', 'Lines, angles, and triangles', 'math', 'geometry', 'LIN_G', 'LIN_G', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('a3870ab3-543d-4a93-9e5f-027808795581', 'Two angles are supplementary. If one angle measures $113°$, what is the measure of the other angle?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$67°$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Supplementary angles sum to $180°$, so the other angle is $180° - 113° = 67°$."},{"id":"B","text":"$77°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This uses $90°$ (complementary) instead of $180°$: $90°$ does not even apply here since $113°$ exceeds $90°$, and the subtraction is also wrong."},{"id":"C","text":"$23°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is $113° - 90°$, treating the angles as complementary, which is impossible since $113°$ is already obtuse."},{"id":"D","text":"$247°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is $360° - 113°$, which would describe a reflex relationship, not supplementary angles."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Supplementary angles have measures that add to $180°$. Therefore the unknown angle equals $180° - 113° = 67°$.', NULL, 'Geometry and Trigonometry', 'Lines, angles, and triangles', 'math', 'geometry', 'LIN_G', 'LIN_G', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('0dc2c21e-977f-4f1b-88c1-4760fc0a2d3a', 'An isosceles triangle has a vertex angle measuring $40°$. Each of the two equal base angles has what measure?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$40°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This repeats the vertex angle; the base angles are equal to each other but not necessarily equal to the vertex angle."},{"id":"B","text":"$50°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is the complement of $40°$ ($90°-40°$), which is not how triangle angles distribute."},{"id":"C","text":"$70°$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The two equal base angles share the remaining $180° - 40° = 140°$, so each is $140° \\div 2 = 70°$."},{"id":"D","text":"$140°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is the combined measure of both base angles ($180°-40°$), not the measure of a single base angle."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'In an isosceles triangle the two base angles are equal. Subtracting the vertex angle leaves $180° - 40° = 140°$ for the two equal angles, so each base angle measures $140° \div 2 = 70°$.', NULL, 'Geometry and Trigonometry', 'Lines, angles, and triangles', 'math', 'geometry', 'LIN_G', 'LIN_G', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('612794e9-6393-4212-885e-0c64cccc9f05', 'Two parallel lines are cut by a transversal. One of the angles formed measures $65°$. What is the measure of its corresponding angle?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$25°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is the complement of $65°$ ($90°-65°$); corresponding angles are not complementary."},{"id":"B","text":"$115°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is the supplement of $65°$ ($180°-65°$), which describes a same-side or linear-pair angle, not the corresponding angle."},{"id":"C","text":"$65°$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. When parallel lines are cut by a transversal, corresponding angles are congruent, so the angle also measures $65°$."},{"id":"D","text":"$130°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This doubles the given angle ($2 \\times 65°$), which has no geometric basis for corresponding angles."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Corresponding angles formed when a transversal crosses two parallel lines are congruent. Since one angle measures $65°$, its corresponding angle also measures $65°$.', NULL, 'Geometry and Trigonometry', 'Lines, angles, and triangles', 'math', 'geometry', 'LIN_G', 'LIN_G', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('2b2820c4-4ada-4a68-97b1-9dcf1a1c3ee6', 'In a right triangle, one of the two acute angles measures $32°$. What is the measure of the other acute angle?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$58°$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The two acute angles of a right triangle are complementary, summing to $90°$, so the other angle is $90° - 32° = 58°$."},{"id":"B","text":"$68°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This results from subtracting $32°$ from $100°$ rather than from the correct total of $90°$."},{"id":"C","text":"$148°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is $180° - 32°$, treating the angles as supplementary instead of using the right angle''s $90°$ constraint."},{"id":"D","text":"$32°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This repeats the given angle, but the two acute angles need not be equal in a general right triangle."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'A right triangle has one $90°$ angle, so the remaining two angles sum to $180° - 90° = 90°$. With one acute angle at $32°$, the other is $90° - 32° = 58°$.', NULL, 'Geometry and Trigonometry', 'Lines, angles, and triangles', 'math', 'geometry', 'LIN_G', 'LIN_G', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('6467681d-1c1d-44be-bc57-61b7b969290c', 'An exterior angle of a triangle measures $120°$. One of the two remote interior angles measures $45°$. What is the measure of the other remote interior angle?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$165°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This adds the two given values ($120°+45°$) instead of using the exterior angle as the sum of the remote interiors."},{"id":"B","text":"$60°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is $180° - 120°$, which gives the adjacent interior angle, not the remaining remote interior angle."},{"id":"C","text":"$75°$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The exterior angle equals the sum of the two remote interior angles, so the other angle is $120° - 45° = 75°$."},{"id":"D","text":"$15°$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This is $60° - 45°$, mistakenly using the adjacent interior angle ($180°-120°$) rather than the exterior angle itself."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The exterior angle theorem states that an exterior angle of a triangle equals the sum of its two remote interior angles. So $120° = 45° + x$, giving $x = 120° - 45° = 75°$.', NULL, 'Geometry and Trigonometry', 'Lines, angles, and triangles', 'math', 'geometry', 'LIN_G', 'LIN_G', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('91fd1a08-412b-4dcb-bcc1-1b61d9f13ab3', 'A linear function $f$ satisfies $f(3) = -2$ and $f(11) = 14$. What is the value of $f(-5)$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$-18$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The slope is $\\frac{14-(-2)}{11-3}=\\frac{16}{8}=2$. Using point $(3,-2)$: $f(x)=2(x-3)-2=2x-8$. Then $f(-5)=2(-5)-8=-18$."},{"id":"B","text":"$-6$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This results from using slope $2$ but writing $f(x)=2x-2$, dropping the correct $y$-intercept of $-8$."},{"id":"C","text":"$2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This comes from finding the slope $2$ and mistakenly reporting it as the function value, confusing rate of change with output."},{"id":"D","text":"$-10$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This uses an incorrect slope of $1$ (miscounting the run as $16$), giving $f(x)=x-5$ and $f(-5)=-10$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The slope between the two given points is $\frac{14-(-2)}{11-3}=\frac{16}{8}=2$. Writing the line through $(3,-2)$: $f(x)=2(x-3)+(-2)=2x-8$. Substituting $x=-5$ gives $f(-5)=2(-5)-8=-10-8=-18$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear functions', 'math', 'algebra', 'LIF', 'LIF', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('f2abad02-0b29-4bb5-8608-a987cf94b286', 'The line $\ell$ in the $xy$-plane passes through the point $(4, 9)$ and is perpendicular to the line defined by $3x + 2y = 12$. The line $\ell$ crosses the $x$-axis at the point $(a, 0)$. What is the value of $a$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$-\\dfrac{19}{2}$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The given line has slope $-\\frac{3}{2}$, so $\\ell$ has slope $\\frac{2}{3}$. Through $(4,9)$: $y-9=\\frac{2}{3}(x-4)$. Setting $y=0$: $-9=\\frac{2}{3}(x-4)$, so $x-4=-\\frac{27}{2}$ and $x=4-\\frac{27}{2}=-\\frac{19}{2}$."},{"id":"B","text":"$\\dfrac{35}{2}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This uses the parallel slope $-\\frac{3}{2}$ instead of the perpendicular slope, giving the wrong line and intercept."},{"id":"C","text":"$-\\dfrac{1}{2}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This results from using slope $2$ (the negative reciprocal of $-\\frac{1}{2}$, not of $-\\frac{3}{2}$), reflecting a misread of the original slope."},{"id":"D","text":"$\\dfrac{59}{3}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This comes from a sign error when isolating $x$: solving $9=\\frac{2}{3}(x-4)$ instead of $-9=\\frac{2}{3}(x-4)$ after setting $y=0$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Rewrite $3x+2y=12$ as $y=-\frac{3}{2}x+6$, slope $-\frac{3}{2}$. The perpendicular slope is the negative reciprocal, $\frac{2}{3}$. Line $\ell$: $y-9=\frac{2}{3}(x-4)$. At the $x$-axis $y=0$: $-9=\frac{2}{3}(x-4)\Rightarrow x-4=-\frac{27}{2}\Rightarrow x=-\frac{19}{2}$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear functions', 'math', 'algebra', 'LIF', 'LIF', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('87574b97-a1f1-45d8-96c3-de2929a7d25e', 'A water tank is being drained at a constant rate. After 6 minutes the tank contains 138 gallons, and after 15 minutes it contains 66 gallons. If draining continues at this same rate, after how many total minutes will the tank contain exactly 18 gallons?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$21$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The rate is $\\frac{66-138}{15-6}=\\frac{-72}{9}=-8$ gallons per minute. Volume: $V=138-8(t-6)=186-8t$. Setting $186-8t=18$ gives $8t=168$, so $t=21$ minutes."},{"id":"B","text":"$24$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This comes from solving $66-8(t-15)=18$ with an arithmetic slip: $8(t-15)=48$ gives $t-15=6$ and $t=21$, but a miscalculation of $48/8=9$ yields $t=24$."},{"id":"C","text":"$18$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This confuses the target gallon amount $18$ with the time, mistaking the volume value for the number of minutes."},{"id":"D","text":"$22$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This uses an incorrect rate of $-7.5$ gal/min (dividing $72$ by an erroneous run of $9.6$), producing $186-7.5t=18$ and $t\\approx 22$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The constant draining rate is $\frac{66-138}{15-6}=\frac{-72}{9}=-8$ gallons per minute. Modeling volume as a linear function of time through $(6,138)$: $V=138-8(t-6)=186-8t$. Set $V=18$: $186-8t=18\Rightarrow 8t=168\Rightarrow t=21$ minutes.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear functions', 'math', 'algebra', 'LIF', 'LIF', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('a307f25e-e0fc-4b2c-8a7c-d7479e777ea7', 'In the $xy$-plane, line $m$ has equation $y = kx + 7$, where $k$ is a constant. Line $m$ passes through the point where the lines $y = 2x - 1$ and $y = -x + 8$ intersect. What is the value of $k$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$-\\dfrac{2}{3}$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The two lines meet where $2x-1=-x+8\\Rightarrow 3x=9\\Rightarrow x=3$, $y=5$. So $(3,5)$ lies on $m$: $5=3k+7\\Rightarrow 3k=-2\\Rightarrow k=-\\frac{2}{3}$."},{"id":"B","text":"$\\dfrac{2}{3}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This drops the sign when solving $5=3k+7$, treating it as $3k=2$ instead of $3k=-2$."},{"id":"C","text":"$4$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This finds the intersection $x$-value incorrectly as the slope, or substitutes the point into $y=kx$ without the $+7$ constant."},{"id":"D","text":"$-2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This results from using only the intersection''s $y$-coordinate as $5=k+7$ (treating $x=1$ instead of $x=3$), giving $k=-2$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Find the intersection of $y=2x-1$ and $y=-x+8$: $2x-1=-x+8\Rightarrow 3x=9\Rightarrow x=3$, and $y=2(3)-1=5$. The point $(3,5)$ lies on $m$, so $5=k(3)+7\Rightarrow 3k=-2\Rightarrow k=-\frac{2}{3}$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear functions', 'math', 'algebra', 'LIF', 'LIF', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('f424f089-dbbd-496f-9835-c1a0b5f73d7f', 'A linear function $g$ is defined by $g(x) = mx + b$. As $x$ increases from $-2$ to $5$, the value of $g$ decreases by $21$, and $g(1) = 4$. What is the value of $b$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$7$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. A decrease of $21$ over a run of $5-(-2)=7$ gives slope $m=\\frac{-21}{7}=-3$. Then $g(1)=-3(1)+b=4$, so $b=4+3=7$."},{"id":"B","text":"$1$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This uses $g(1)=-3+b=4$ but solves it as $b=4-3=1$, a sign error when moving the $-3$ across the equation."},{"id":"C","text":"$4$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This mistakes the given value $g(1)=4$ for the $y$-intercept, ignoring that the intercept is $g(0)$, not $g(1)$."},{"id":"D","text":"$-3$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This reports the slope $m=-3$ as the intercept $b$, confusing the two parameters of the line."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The function decreases by $21$ over a run of $5-(-2)=7$, so slope $m=\frac{-21}{7}=-3$. Using $g(1)=4$: $-3(1)+b=4\Rightarrow b=4+3=7$. So $g(x)=-3x+7$ and $b=7$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear functions', 'math', 'algebra', 'LIF', 'LIF', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('26f686b7-5ce1-406c-a685-4f7e886b3bdb', 'Two car rental companies charge a flat fee plus a per-mile rate. Company A charges \$45 plus \$0.30 per mile. Company B charges \$75 plus \$0.18 per mile. For a trip of $d$ miles, the two companies cost the same. For trips longer than $d$ miles, which company is cheaper, and what is $d$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Company B is cheaper; $d = 250$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Setting $45+0.30d=75+0.18d$ gives $0.12d=30$, so $d=250$. Beyond $250$ miles, B''s lower per-mile rate ($0.18<0.30$) makes it cheaper."},{"id":"B","text":"Company A is cheaper; $d = 250$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect on the comparison. The break-even of $250$ is right, but past it the company with the smaller per-mile rate (B, at \\$0.18) is cheaper, not A."},{"id":"C","text":"Company B is cheaper; $d = 100$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect $d$. This divides $30$ by $0.30$ instead of by the rate difference $0.12$, giving $100$ rather than $250$."},{"id":"D","text":"Company A is cheaper; $d = 360$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This uses the wrong rate difference (dividing $30$ by roughly $0.083$) and also misidentifies the cheaper company beyond break-even."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Set the costs equal: $45+0.30d=75+0.18d$. Subtract: $0.30d-0.18d=75-45$, so $0.12d=30$ and $d=250$ miles. For $d>250$, Company B''s smaller per-mile rate of \$0.18 (versus \$0.30) wins, so Company B is cheaper.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear functions', 'math', 'algebra', 'LIF', 'LIF', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('a2d102ff-4e7c-4a4e-a6b2-cdc137d67d36', 'Line $p$ in the $xy$-plane passes through the points $(-3, t)$ and $(5, t + 20)$. If line $p$ also passes through the origin, what is the value of $t$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$-\\dfrac{15}{2}$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. The slope of $p$ is $\\frac{(t+20)-t}{5-(-3)}=\\frac{20}{8}=\\frac{5}{2}$. A line through the origin with this slope is $y=\\frac{5}{2}x$. At $x=-3$: $t=\\frac{5}{2}(-3)=-\\frac{15}{2}$."},{"id":"B","text":"$\\dfrac{15}{2}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This drops the negative sign from $x=-3$, computing $\\frac{5}{2}(3)$ instead of $\\frac{5}{2}(-3)$."},{"id":"C","text":"$\\dfrac{25}{2}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This evaluates the origin-line at $x=5$ instead of $x=-3$, giving $\\frac{5}{2}(5)=\\frac{25}{2}=t+20$, then mishandles the equation."},{"id":"D","text":"$-\\dfrac{20}{3}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This inverts the slope to $\\frac{8}{20}=\\frac{2}{5}$ and then misapplies it, or swaps rise and run when computing the slope."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The slope of line $p$ is $\frac{(t+20)-t}{5-(-3)}=\frac{20}{8}=\frac{5}{2}$. Since the line passes through the origin, its equation is $y=\frac{5}{2}x$. The point $(-3,t)$ lies on it, so $t=\frac{5}{2}(-3)=-\frac{15}{2}$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear functions', 'math', 'algebra', 'LIF', 'LIF', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('ecac88c2-3d19-490b-891a-2b141045099e', 'The graph of a linear function $h$ in the $xy$-plane has a positive slope and a positive $y$-intercept. The function satisfies $h(0) + h(4) = 26$ and $h(4) - h(0) = 12$. What is the slope of the graph of $h$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$3$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Adding and subtracting: $2h(4)=38\\Rightarrow h(4)=19$ and $2h(0)=14\\Rightarrow h(0)=7$. Slope $=\\frac{h(4)-h(0)}{4-0}=\\frac{12}{4}=3$, which is positive, consistent with $h(0)=7>0$."},{"id":"B","text":"$12$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This takes $h(4)-h(0)=12$ as the slope directly, forgetting to divide the change in output by the change in input ($4-0=4$)."},{"id":"C","text":"$\\dfrac{13}{2}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This uses $\\frac{26}{4}$ or $h(0)=13$ as a slope, misapplying the sum equation $h(0)+h(4)=26$."},{"id":"D","text":"$\\dfrac{19}{4}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect. This divides $h(4)=19$ by $4$, treating the value of $h(4)$ as the rise over the full run instead of the difference $h(4)-h(0)$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'From $h(0)+h(4)=26$ and $h(4)-h(0)=12$, add to get $2h(4)=38$, so $h(4)=19$; subtract to get $2h(0)=14$, so $h(0)=7$. The slope is $\frac{h(4)-h(0)}{4-0}=\frac{19-7}{4}=\frac{12}{4}=3$.', NULL, 'Algebra', 'Linear functions', 'math', 'algebra', 'LIF', 'LIF', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('b039635a-8644-44fc-a62e-67d35f7c5a92', 'The expression $\dfrac{6x^2 + x - 12}{2x + 3}$ is equivalent to which of the following for all $x$ where the expression is defined?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$3x - 4$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Factoring the numerator: $6x^2 + x - 12 = (2x + 3)(3x - 4)$, since $(2x)(3x)=6x^2$, $(2x)(-4)+(3)(3x)=-8x+9x=x$, and $(3)(-4)=-12$. Cancelling $(2x+3)$ leaves $3x - 4$."},{"id":"B","text":"$3x + 4$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from mis-signing the constant factor; the correct factor is $-4$ because $(3)(-4)=-12$, not $+12$."},{"id":"C","text":"$2x - 4$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses the wrong leading factor; the numerator''s $6x^2$ requires a $3x$ term after dividing by $2x$, not $2x$."},{"id":"D","text":"$6x - 12$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the numerator with the middle term dropped and not divided by $2x+3$; it does not equal the original quotient."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Factor the numerator as a product including the denominator: $6x^2 + x - 12 = (2x+3)(3x-4)$ because $(2x)(3x)=6x^2$, the cross terms give $-8x + 9x = x$, and $(3)(-4) = -12$. Dividing by $2x+3$ yields $3x - 4$.', NULL, 'Advanced Math', 'Equivalent expressions', 'math', 'advanced', 'EQS', 'EQS', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('ed3f9986-f704-46fc-a4a2-8b7ce9187b2f', 'Which of the following is equivalent to $\dfrac{1}{x - 2} - \dfrac{4}{x^2 - 4}$ for all defined values of $x$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$\\dfrac{1}{x + 2}$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Since $x^2-4=(x-2)(x+2)$, the common denominator is $(x-2)(x+2)$. The first fraction becomes $\\frac{x+2}{(x-2)(x+2)}$, so the numerator is $(x+2)-4 = x-2$. Cancelling gives $\\frac{x-2}{(x-2)(x+2)}=\\frac{1}{x+2}$."},{"id":"B","text":"$\\dfrac{1}{x - 2}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This would require the numerator to reduce to $x+2$; instead it reduces to $x-2$, cancelling with the $(x-2)$ factor, not $(x+2)$."},{"id":"C","text":"$\\dfrac{-3}{x^2 - 4}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This treats $\\frac{1}{x-2}$ as $\\frac{1}{x^2-4}$, failing to convert it to the common denominator $\\frac{x+2}{x^2-4}$."},{"id":"D","text":"$\\dfrac{x + 6}{x^2 - 4}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds the two numerators instead of subtracting; the correct numerator is $(x+2)-4=x-2$, not $(x+2)+4$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Factor $x^2-4=(x-2)(x+2)$. Rewrite over the common denominator: $\frac{x+2}{(x-2)(x+2)} - \frac{4}{(x-2)(x+2)} = \frac{(x+2)-4}{(x-2)(x+2)} = \frac{x-2}{(x-2)(x+2)} = \frac{1}{x+2}$.', NULL, 'Advanced Math', 'Equivalent expressions', 'math', 'advanced', 'EQS', 'EQS', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('d10bea39-bca7-4c2d-af97-216b37e28b15', 'If $a > 0$, which of the following is equivalent to $\left(a^{3/4}\right)^2 \cdot a^{-1/2}$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$a$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Apply power rules: $(a^{3/4})^2 = a^{3/2}$, then $a^{3/2}\\cdot a^{-1/2} = a^{3/2 - 1/2} = a^{1} = a$."},{"id":"B","text":"$a^2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds exponents incorrectly as $3/2 + 1/2$ instead of $3/2 + (-1/2)$; the $-1/2$ exponent must be subtracted."},{"id":"C","text":"$\\sqrt{a}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This corresponds to exponent $1/2$, which would arise from $(a^{3/4})^2 = a^{3/4+2}$ or another mishandling; the correct combined exponent is $1$."},{"id":"D","text":"$a^{3/4}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This ignores the squaring and the $a^{-1/2}$ factor entirely; both operations change the exponent."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Use $(a^{m})^n=a^{mn}$ and $a^m\cdot a^n=a^{m+n}$: $(a^{3/4})^2=a^{3/2}$, and $a^{3/2}\cdot a^{-1/2}=a^{3/2-1/2}=a^1=a$.', NULL, 'Advanced Math', 'Equivalent expressions', 'math', 'advanced', 'EQS', 'EQS', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('0499b384-7a84-469a-ae79-cfa429ea973b', 'The expression $(2x - 5)(3x + 1) - (x - 4)(6x + 2)$ is equivalent to which of the following?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$9x - 13$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Expand: $(2x-5)(3x+1)=6x^2-13x-5$ and $(x-4)(6x+2)=6x^2-22x-8$. Subtracting: $(6x^2-13x-5)-(6x^2-22x-8)=9x+3$. Wait—recompute carefully: $-13x-(-22x)=9x$ and $-5-(-8)=3$, giving $9x+3$. The intended distractor set uses $9x+3$; correct constant is $+3$."},{"id":"B","text":"$9x + 3$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Expand each product: $(2x-5)(3x+1)=6x^2-13x-5$ and $(x-4)(6x+2)=6x^2-22x-8$. The $6x^2$ terms cancel; $-13x-(-22x)=9x$ and $-5-(-8)=+3$, giving $9x+3$."},{"id":"C","text":"$-9x - 3$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This results from subtracting the products in the wrong order; reversing the subtraction negates every term of the correct answer $9x+3$."},{"id":"D","text":"$12x^2 - 35x - 13$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds the two products instead of subtracting, so the $6x^2$ terms fail to cancel; subtraction is required."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Expand: $(2x-5)(3x+1)=6x^2-13x-5$ and $(x-4)(6x+2)=6x^2-22x-8$. Subtracting the second from the first cancels $6x^2$: $-13x-(-22x)=9x$ and $-5-(-8)=+3$, so the result is $9x+3$.', NULL, 'Advanced Math', 'Equivalent expressions', 'math', 'advanced', 'EQS', 'EQS', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('cd4ef725-2a5e-433f-a4d3-eeb371144da4', 'Which of the following is equivalent to $\dfrac{x^{-1} + y^{-1}}{x^{-1}y^{-1}}$ for all nonzero $x$ and $y$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$x + y$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Multiply numerator and denominator by $xy$: numerator $(x^{-1}+y^{-1})\\cdot xy = y + x$; denominator $(x^{-1}y^{-1})\\cdot xy = 1$. So the expression equals $x+y$."},{"id":"B","text":"$\\dfrac{1}{x + y}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the reciprocal of the correct result; it would arise from inverting the simplified fraction."},{"id":"C","text":"$xy(x + y)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This multiplies by an extra factor of $xy$; clearing the negative exponents leaves a denominator of $1$, not $\\frac{1}{xy}$."},{"id":"D","text":"$\\dfrac{x + y}{xy}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This treats the denominator $x^{-1}y^{-1}$ as $xy$ rather than $\\frac{1}{xy}$; dividing by $\\frac{1}{xy}$ multiplies by $xy$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Rewrite using positive exponents: $\frac{\frac{1}{x}+\frac{1}{y}}{\frac{1}{xy}}$. The numerator is $\frac{y+x}{xy}$, and dividing by $\frac{1}{xy}$ multiplies by $xy$: $\frac{x+y}{xy}\cdot xy = x+y$.', NULL, 'Advanced Math', 'Equivalent expressions', 'math', 'advanced', 'EQS', 'EQS', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('5b106ebb-a1a1-48e8-b6bf-64292974473a', 'For all $x > 0$, the expression $\sqrt{50x^3} - \sqrt{8x^3}$ is equivalent to which of the following?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$3x\\sqrt{2x}$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Simplify each radical: $\\sqrt{50x^3}=\\sqrt{25x^2}\\cdot\\sqrt{2x}=5x\\sqrt{2x}$ and $\\sqrt{8x^3}=\\sqrt{4x^2}\\cdot\\sqrt{2x}=2x\\sqrt{2x}$. Subtracting like radicals: $5x\\sqrt{2x}-2x\\sqrt{2x}=3x\\sqrt{2x}$."},{"id":"B","text":"$\\sqrt{42x^3}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This subtracts the radicands ($50-8=42$), which is invalid; radicals cannot be combined by subtracting under the root."},{"id":"C","text":"$3x^2\\sqrt{2}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This mishandles the odd power: $x^3=x^2\\cdot x$, so one factor of $x$ stays under the radical, giving $\\sqrt{2x}$, not $x\\sqrt 2$."},{"id":"D","text":"$7x\\sqrt{2x}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds the coefficients $5x$ and $2x$ instead of subtracting; the operation between the terms is subtraction."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Factor perfect squares: $\sqrt{50x^3}=5x\sqrt{2x}$ and $\sqrt{8x^3}=2x\sqrt{2x}$. These are like radicals, so $5x\sqrt{2x}-2x\sqrt{2x}=3x\sqrt{2x}$.', NULL, 'Advanced Math', 'Equivalent expressions', 'math', 'advanced', 'EQS', 'EQS', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('8af32491-0366-4cef-93cb-103c3d7e6bd6', 'The expression $\dfrac{2}{x + h} - \dfrac{2}{x}$, where $h \neq 0$, is equivalent to which of the following?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$\\dfrac{-2h}{x(x + h)}$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Use common denominator $x(x+h)$: $\\frac{2x}{x(x+h)} - \\frac{2(x+h)}{x(x+h)} = \\frac{2x - 2x - 2h}{x(x+h)} = \\frac{-2h}{x(x+h)}$."},{"id":"B","text":"$\\dfrac{2h}{x(x + h)}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This has the wrong sign; the numerator is $2x-(2x+2h)=-2h$, which is negative, not positive."},{"id":"C","text":"$\\dfrac{0}{x(x+h)}=0$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This incorrectly cancels the $-2h$; the $x$ terms cancel but the $-2h$ remains, so the expression is not zero."},{"id":"D","text":"$\\dfrac{-2h}{x + h}$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This drops a factor of $x$ from the denominator; the common denominator is $x(x+h)$, not just $x+h$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Over the common denominator $x(x+h)$: $\frac{2x}{x(x+h)} - \frac{2(x+h)}{x(x+h)} = \frac{2x - 2x - 2h}{x(x+h)} = \frac{-2h}{x(x+h)}$.', NULL, 'Advanced Math', 'Equivalent expressions', 'math', 'advanced', 'EQS', 'EQS', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('351be8ff-18f8-450f-879e-0e75aaba3feb', 'If $k$ is a constant and $4x^2 + kx + 9$ is the square of a binomial with positive coefficients, what is the value of $k$, and to what does the expression simplify?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$k = 12$, and the expression equals $(2x + 3)^2$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"A perfect square trinomial $(2x+3)^2 = 4x^2 + 2(2x)(3) + 9 = 4x^2 + 12x + 9$. Matching gives $k=12$ with positive coefficients."},{"id":"B","text":"$k = 6$, and the expression equals $(2x + 3)^2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"The middle term of $(2x+3)^2$ is $2(2x)(3)=12x$, not $6x$; $k=6$ would not produce a perfect square."},{"id":"C","text":"$k = 36$, and the expression equals $(2x + 3)^2$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This multiplies the binomial constants as $2x\\cdot3\\cdot? $ incorrectly; the cross term is $2(2)(3)=12$, so $k=12$, not $36$."},{"id":"D","text":"$k = 13$, and the expression equals $(4x + 9)(x + 1)$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"$(4x+9)(x+1)=4x^2+13x+9$ is not a perfect square (a square requires equal binomial factors), so it does not meet the condition."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'For $4x^2+kx+9$ to be a perfect square with positive coefficients, it must equal $(2x+3)^2$ since $(2x)^2=4x^2$ and $3^2=9$. The middle term is $2(2x)(3)=12x$, so $k=12$.', NULL, 'Advanced Math', 'Equivalent expressions', 'math', 'advanced', 'EQS', 'EQS', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('da0bae36-943a-4bce-b28c-d59951e511fc', 'A jacket that normally costs $80 is on sale for 25% off. What is the sale price of the jacket?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$20","is_correct":false,"explanation":"$20 is 25% of $80, which is the discount amount, not the sale price. The sale price is what remains after subtracting the discount."},{"id":"B","text":"$55","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This subtracts an incorrect discount; 25% of $80 is $20, not $25, so subtracting $25 gives $55 in error."},{"id":"C","text":"$60","is_correct":true,"explanation":"25% of $80 is $0.25 \\times 80 = 20$, so the sale price is $80 - 20 = 60$ dollars."},{"id":"D","text":"$100","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds the 25% as if it were a markup ($80 + $20$) instead of subtracting it as a discount."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'A 25% discount removes 25% of the original price. The discount is $0.25 \times 80 = 20$ dollars. Subtracting from the original price gives a sale price of $80 - 20 = 60$ dollars.', 'Find 25% of $80 first, then subtract it from the original price.', 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'Percentages', 'math', 'psda', 'PER', 'PER', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('756ca817-8d96-4ad1-b238-9285fee5d255', 'In a class of 40 students, 30% of the students play a musical instrument. How many students in the class play a musical instrument?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"10","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is 25% of 40, not 30%. It comes from dividing 40 by 4 rather than multiplying by 0.30."},{"id":"B","text":"12","is_correct":true,"explanation":"30% of 40 is $0.30 \\times 40 = 12$ students."},{"id":"C","text":"13","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This rounds or miscounts; $0.30 \\times 40 = 12$ exactly, so 13 is incorrect."},{"id":"D","text":"28","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the number who do NOT play an instrument ($40 - 12 = 28$), not the number who do."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'To find 30% of 40, multiply: $0.30 \times 40 = 12$. So 12 students play a musical instrument.', 'Convert 30% to the decimal 0.30 and multiply by the total number of students.', 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'Percentages', 'math', 'psda', 'PER', 'PER', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('289abb8f-03c4-4e03-90b1-e59918ca6fa0', 'A student answered 18 out of 24 questions correctly on a quiz. What percent of the questions did the student answer correctly?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"60%","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This would be the percent if 18 out of 30 were correct; $18/24$ actually equals 0.75, not 0.60."},{"id":"B","text":"72%","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is an incorrect computation; $18 \\div 24 = 0.75$, which is 75%, not 72%."},{"id":"C","text":"75%","is_correct":true,"explanation":"The fraction correct is $18/24 = 0.75$, which equals 75%."},{"id":"D","text":"80%","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This would require about 19.2 correct out of 24; $18/24 = 0.75 = 75\\%$, not 80%."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The percent correct is the number correct divided by the total: $\frac{18}{24} = 0.75$. Converting to a percent gives $0.75 \times 100 = 75\%$.', 'Divide the number correct by the total number of questions, then convert to a percent.', 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'Percentages', 'math', 'psda', 'PER', 'PER', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('8c80d91a-4625-44d0-adea-ffb1031bf798', 'A water tank holds 50 gallons when full. It is currently 40% full. How many gallons of water are in the tank?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"10","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is 20% of 50, not 40%. It results from multiplying by 0.20 instead of 0.40."},{"id":"B","text":"20","is_correct":true,"explanation":"40% of 50 is $0.40 \\times 50 = 20$ gallons."},{"id":"C","text":"30","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This is the amount of empty space (60% of 50), not the water present."},{"id":"D","text":"40","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This mistakes the percent itself (40) for the number of gallons; the correct amount is $0.40 \\times 50 = 20$."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The amount of water is 40% of the tank''s capacity: $0.40 \times 50 = 20$ gallons.', 'Multiply the full capacity by 0.40 to find the current amount.', 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'Percentages', 'math', 'psda', 'PER', 'PER', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('e2e412ca-1167-4688-8661-eed06c927261', 'A pair of headphones costs $90 before tax. A sales tax of 8% is added to the price. What is the total cost of the headphones, including tax?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$7.20","is_correct":false,"explanation":"$7.20 is only the tax amount ($0.08 \\times 90$), not the total cost including the original price."},{"id":"B","text":"$82.80","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This subtracts the tax instead of adding it; tax increases the price, giving $90 + 7.20$, not $90 - 7.20$."},{"id":"C","text":"$97.20","is_correct":true,"explanation":"The tax is $0.08 \\times 90 = 7.20$, so the total is $90 + 7.20 = 97.20$ dollars."},{"id":"D","text":"$162.00","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds 80% ($72) instead of 8%; the tax rate is 8%, giving a tax of $7.20$."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The tax is 8% of $90: $0.08 \times 90 = 7.20$ dollars. Adding the tax to the original price gives $90 + 7.20 = 97.20$ dollars. (Equivalently, $1.08 \times 90 = 97.20$.)', 'Find 8% of $90 and add it to the original price.', 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'Percentages', 'math', 'psda', 'PER', 'PER', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('48484837-3cba-468f-a3fd-6fef4f251e35', 'The population of a small town increased from 200 people to 250 people over one year. By what percent did the population increase?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"20%","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This divides the increase by the new population ($50/250$) instead of the original; percent increase uses the original amount."},{"id":"B","text":"25%","is_correct":true,"explanation":"The increase is $250 - 200 = 50$, and $50/200 = 0.25 = 25\\%$."},{"id":"C","text":"50%","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses the raw increase of 50 as the percent, ignoring that it must be compared to the original 200."},{"id":"D","text":"125%","is_correct":false,"explanation":"125% is the new population as a percent of the original ($250/200$), not the percent of increase."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Percent increase equals the increase divided by the original amount. The increase is $250 - 200 = 50$, so the percent increase is $\frac{50}{200} = 0.25 = 25\%$.', 'Find the amount of increase, then divide by the ORIGINAL population, not the new one.', 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'Percentages', 'math', 'psda', 'PER', 'PER', 'easy', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('d957c726-fa52-446f-89b1-35baaaf1ef43', 'A data set consists of 7 positive integers. Six of the values are 4, 9, 11, 11, 14, and 21, which sum to 70. The seventh value, $k$, satisfies $4 \leq k \leq 14$, and when $k$ is included the median of the 7 values is 11. For the mean of all 7 values to equal the median, what must $k$ equal?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"If $k=5$, the sum is $70+5=75$ and the mean is $75/7 \\approx 10.71$, which is not equal to the median 11."},{"id":"B","text":"$7$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"If $k=7$, the sum is $70+7=77$ and the mean is $77/7 = 11$, exactly equal to the median 11. The ordered set 4, 7, 9, 11, 11, 14, 21 has 4th value (median) 11, so all conditions hold."},{"id":"C","text":"$9$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"If $k=9$, the sum is $70+9=79$ and the mean is $79/7 \\approx 11.29$, which exceeds the median 11."},{"id":"D","text":"$11$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"If $k=11$, the sum is $70+11=81$ and the mean is $81/7 \\approx 11.57$, which is not equal to the median 11."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The six known values sum to $4+9+11+11+14+21 = 70$. With the median fixed at 11, set the mean equal to the median: $\frac{70+k}{7} = 11$. Then $70+k = 77$, so $k = 7$. Checking: the ordered set 4, 7, 9, 11, 11, 14, 21 has median (4th value) 11 and mean $77/7 = 11$, satisfying every condition. Since $4 \leq 7 \leq 14$, $k=7$ is valid.', NULL, 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'One-variable data', 'math', 'psda', 'OIA', 'OIA', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('4d3ed557-ec12-44cd-a28e-497075c4e3ce', 'Two data sets, $P$ and $Q$, each contain 50 values. Set $P$ has a mean of 60 and a standard deviation of 4. Set $Q$ is created by multiplying every value in $P$ by 2 and then subtracting 30. What are the mean and standard deviation of set $Q$?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Mean $90$, standard deviation $8$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"A linear transformation $y = 2x - 30$ scales the mean by 2 and shifts it: $2(60)-30 = 90$. Standard deviation is unaffected by the additive shift but scaled by $|2|$: $2(4)=8$."},{"id":"B","text":"Mean $90$, standard deviation $5$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"The mean $90$ is correct, but the standard deviation must be multiplied by the absolute value of the scale factor 2, giving 8, not 5. The $-30$ shift does not affect spread."},{"id":"C","text":"Mean $120$, standard deviation $8$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This ignores the subtraction of 30. The mean is $2(60)-30 = 90$, not $2(60)=120$. The standard deviation 8 is correct."},{"id":"D","text":"Mean $90$, standard deviation $-22$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Standard deviation cannot be negative. This incorrectly applies the full transformation $2(4)-30 = -22$ to the standard deviation; the additive constant does not affect spread, and the scale factor gives $2(4)=8$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'For a linear transformation $y = ax + b$ applied to every value, the mean transforms as $\bar{y} = a\bar{x} + b$ and the standard deviation transforms as $\sigma_y = |a|\sigma_x$. Here $a=2$, $b=-30$. Mean: $2(60) - 30 = 120 - 30 = 90$. Standard deviation: the shift of $-30$ moves every value equally and does not change spread, while the factor 2 doubles the spread, so $\sigma_Q = |2|(4) = 8$.', NULL, 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'One-variable data', 'math', 'psda', 'OIA', 'OIA', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('4e6637db-c6f5-43a9-9087-286e4313f75e', 'A list of 5 distinct integers has a mean of 20, a median of 18, and a range of 24. The smallest value is 8. What is the largest possible value of the second-smallest integer in the list?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$13$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This value is achievable but not the maximum. With second-smallest 13, the constraints can be met, but the second-smallest can be pushed higher (up to 17) while keeping the median at 18 and total at 100."},{"id":"B","text":"$17$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"The five integers in order are $8, b, 18, d, 32$ (range 24 means max $=8+24=32$, and median is 18). The sum is $20\\times5=100$, so $b+d = 100-8-18-32 = 42$. To maximize $b$, minimize $d$; since $d>18$ and distinct, the smallest valid $d$ paired with the largest $b<18$ gives $b=17, d=25$. The list $8, 17, 18, 25, 32$ is valid, so $b=17$ is the maximum."},{"id":"C","text":"$18$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"The second-smallest must be strictly less than the median 18 because the integers are distinct, so it cannot equal 18. The maximum is 17."},{"id":"D","text":"$24$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This exceeds the median 18; the second-smallest value must be less than the middle value in an ordered list of distinct integers, so 24 is impossible."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Order the 5 distinct integers as $a<b<c<d<e$. Given $a=8$, median $c=18$, range $e-a=24$ so $e=8+24=32$. The mean is 20, so the sum is $5\times20=100$. Then $b+d = 100 - 8 - 18 - 32 = 42$. To maximize $b$, minimize $d$, but $d$ must satisfy $18 < d$ and $b<18$, all distinct integers. The largest allowed $b$ is 17, forcing $d = 42-17 = 25 > 18$, valid. The list $8, 17, 18, 25, 32$ satisfies every condition, so the maximum second-smallest value is $17$.', NULL, 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'One-variable data', 'math', 'psda', 'OIA', 'OIA', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('8e124dbe-60ce-4b89-a5aa-c8ab3b747f61', 'In a data set of 100 values, the mean is 50. A statistician discovers that two values were recorded incorrectly: one value entered as 30 should have been 45, and another value entered as 80 should have been 20. After correcting both errors, what is the new mean of the data set?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"$49.55$","is_correct":true,"explanation":"The original sum is $100\\times50 = 5000$. Corrections change the sum by $(45-30)+(20-80) = 15 + (-60) = -45$. New sum $= 5000-45 = 4955$, and new mean $= 4955/100 = 49.55$."},{"id":"B","text":"$50.45$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This adds 45 to the sum instead of subtracting. The net change is $(45-30)+(20-80) = -45$, so the new sum is $4955$, giving a mean of 49.55, not 50.45."},{"id":"C","text":"$50.00$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This assumes the corrections cancel out. They do not: $+15$ and $-60$ sum to $-45$, a net decrease, so the mean must drop below 50."},{"id":"D","text":"$49.85$","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This uses an incorrect net change of $-15$ (only counting the first correction). The total change is $15 - 60 = -45$, giving mean $49.55$."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The original total is $100 \times 50 = 5000$. The first correction raises a value from 30 to 45, a change of $+15$. The second correction lowers a value from 80 to 20, a change of $-60$. Net change to the sum: $15 - 60 = -45$. New sum $= 5000 - 45 = 4955$. With 100 values still, the new mean is $\frac{4955}{100} = 49.55$.', NULL, 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'One-variable data', 'math', 'psda', 'OIA', 'OIA', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('7b5f6b69-8e1b-4b37-a159-6aef0556b67b', 'Data set X and data set Y each contain the same number of values and have the same mean. The values in X are clustered tightly around the mean, while the values in Y are spread far from the mean. One additional value, exactly equal to the common mean, is added to BOTH sets. Which statement must be true about the resulting standard deviations?', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Both standard deviations decrease, and X still has a smaller standard deviation than Y.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Adding a value equal to the mean keeps the mean unchanged and adds 0 to the sum of squared deviations while increasing the count, so each standard deviation strictly decreases. Since Y''s squared deviations remain larger, X stays smaller than Y."},{"id":"B","text":"Both standard deviations stay exactly the same.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Standard deviation uses the sum of squared deviations divided by the count. Adding a value at the mean leaves the numerator unchanged but increases the denominator, so the standard deviation strictly decreases for both sets, not stays the same."},{"id":"C","text":"The standard deviation of Y becomes smaller than that of X.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Adding a value at the mean reduces both standard deviations via the same divisor effect but cannot reverse their order, since Y''s squared deviations remain larger than X''s. Y stays larger than X."},{"id":"D","text":"Both standard deviations increase because the data set is now larger.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"A larger count does not increase standard deviation by itself. The added value contributes zero squared deviation while enlarging the denominator, so both standard deviations decrease, not increase."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Standard deviation is $\sqrt{\frac{\sum (x_i-\bar{x})^2}{n}}$. Adding one value equal to the mean $\bar{x}$ keeps the mean unchanged and contributes $(\bar{x}-\bar{x})^2 = 0$ to the numerator, while increasing $n$ by 1. Thus $\frac{\sum(x_i-\bar{x})^2}{n}$ strictly decreases for both sets, so both standard deviations decrease. Because Y''s values are farther from the mean, its sum of squared deviations is larger than X''s, and this ordering is preserved after dividing by the same enlarged count. Therefore X''s standard deviation remains smaller than Y''s.', NULL, 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'One-variable data', 'math', 'psda', 'OIA', 'OIA', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
VALUES ('7710da2f-9f83-4195-a362-9c8fd43783b0', 'A teacher records the quiz scores of 9 students. In increasing order the scores are 12, 15, 15, 18, 20, 22, 25, 28, and an unknown highest score $m$, where $m \geq 28$. The teacher notes that changing $m$ to any larger value has no effect on one particular measure of the data. Which measure is unaffected, and why?', 'Ordered scores (9 students): 12, 15, 15, 18, 20, 22, 25, 28, m, with m ≥ 28.', '[{"id":"A","text":"The median, because it is the 5th value (20) and remains 20 no matter how large $m$ becomes.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"With 9 values, the median is the 5th in order. Since $m\\geq28$ keeps $m$ as the largest value, the ordered positions of the first eight scores never change, so the 5th value stays 20 regardless of $m$."},{"id":"B","text":"The mean, because adding more to $m$ is balanced by the other eight values.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"The mean is $\\frac{155+m}{9}$, where the first eight scores sum to 155. Increasing $m$ directly increases this sum and therefore the mean; it is not balanced by the other values, which are fixed."},{"id":"C","text":"The range, because the minimum value 12 is fixed.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"The range is $m - 12$. Although the minimum 12 is fixed, increasing $m$ increases the range, so the range is affected, not unchanged."},{"id":"D","text":"The standard deviation, because $m$ is already the largest value.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Increasing $m$ pushes the largest value farther from the mean and raises the mean, increasing the spread, so the standard deviation increases rather than staying constant."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'For an ordered list of 9 values, the median is in position $\frac{9+1}{2}=5$. The first eight scores are fixed, and the constraint $m\geq28$ guarantees $m$ stays in the 9th (largest) position, so the lower eight values keep their order. The 5th value is 20, so the median is 20 regardless of $m$. By contrast, the mean $\frac{155+m}{9}$, the range $m-12$, and the standard deviation all change as $m$ increases. Only the median is unaffected.', NULL, 'Problem-Solving and Data Analysis', 'One-variable data', 'math', 'psda', 'OIA', 'OIA', 'hard', true, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
COMMIT;
